data.jamchartnote: An early 2019 fan favorite. After a typical rocking Yeti start, band brings it down at the 8 minute mark and finds a gorgeous, repeating theme that they carry into a gentle, blissful finish.

data.footnote: With Axel F teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: BLISTERING debut is breakneck speed and has a reprise of the chorus to end the song. Slick "Axel F" teases from Rick.

data.footnote: With Magic School Bus Theme teases.
data.jamchartnote: Breaks into an awesome funk jam that leads into "Magic School Bus" teasing. Eventually makes a major pivot soars through a great peak.
Different arrangement than we'll see after its 2021 revival, but really cool to peek into an early version of "SOS." Still has that same arena rock peak - except it was played in a tiny club.

Upon departure from song proper, Peter lays down a HEAVY layer of guitar while Rick vamps in major key, giving the otherwise standard jam a really cool feel. Peter then switches to keys as they hit a pleasant space for the remainder.
Might have you thinking you're listening on 1.5x speed. Breakneck pace and explosive first peak leads to some serious shredding from Peter in the second jam.
Most long-time Goose fans likely have Rick's guitar solo memorized. The PERFECT standard version of this song from a landmark show.

Gorgeous groove (repeated in 12/6/19 "GB Rap") builds in intensity w/out losing its beauty. Glory peak at 11 ends with Rick returning to earlier groove. Shifts into more rocking style allowing more focus on each member before melting > Indian River.
Impossible not to listen to this version without a huge smile on your face. High-spirited, happy and melodic jamming with a fun peak.

Prime Grade A Rock & Roll. Phenomenal, collective, patient build-up to an absolutely ferocious frenzy in the 16/17th minute, followed by brilliant jazzy cool down. Must hear jam from must hear 2019 show.

Melodic first jam gives way to a cowbell-driven, spacey jam. Trevor and Rick trade counterpoints until Trevor's soaring bass lines propel them to a beautiful peak! Not content, the band digs into a dirty groove to bring it home.

Monster AIN w/ multiple amazing movements. Pete opens things with incredible synth work, but Spuds is the real star; driving this monster jam towards a magnificent melodic peak! Some very funky playing from Richk closes this all-timer.

The Buffalo Arcadia: An iconic fan favourite. Rick's bright rhythm playing spurs Peter into an uplifting bliss segment early on, which leads to several minutes of sustained soloing. Seemingly ends and then gets revived by the band for another extended run around pure euphoria before returning home. Recommended for a sunny afternoon.
Short, pretty jam that finishes with a wonderful return to the Indian River riff.

After a fairly standard first jam, second jam picks up in the 11th minute and no one could predict would follow as Goose launches into their longest, most exploratory jam to date (and only 30 min+ jam pre-2022) that caps off an all-time 4-song set.
Serene, watery textures throughout. Perfect early example of patiently building a jam in bliss without needing to glory peak it.
High energy, relentless jam that never lets up and ends in a mammoth shredfest peak.
Tumblefest! Very fun Tumble>Make the Move>Tumble>Cantaloupe Island>Tumble sandwich.

data.footnote: Run DMC. With "Stage Plot" and "Goo" jams.
data.jamchartnote: Great segue out of Drive leads to one of the most unexpected jams of 2019. Jam starts with almost a "Stage Plot" and "Goo" vocal jam, followed by Rick hitting the same beautiful groove found in the 9/6/2019 Wysteria, and ending in magnificent fashion.
Nonstop dance party until they step on the gas in the last 5 minutes resulting in a fun, thrilling finish.

A twisting “fast Need” with a danceable exploratory initial jam that pivots over a drum break into a more dynamic guitar-led section. As Rick passes the baton to Trevor, they descend into an almost marching section with a syncopated drum line and thumping bassline. Rick finds a new melody that the band quickly backs as a looping hook that naturally summons the composed tail.

Might as well call this “Tremble,” with the entirety of the jam built on Trevor’s thumping bass line. After an unusually fast-paced composed head, the two-section improv begins with Rick exploring morphing loops before dropping into a slightly twangy almost southern rock jam.

Efficient Pete-led 14-minute journey initiated by his vibesy accompaniment as Rick arpeggiates out of the head section. A soaring synth jam that starts bright and clean morphs into a grittier sawtoothy lead section before landing them into a floating full-band jam with sort of “Scarlet”-islandy motif undergirded by rolling drum fills and well-placed Trevor flair. Rick leads out from there with a punchy attack that twists the tropical theme into a short but assertive closing statement.

data.footnote: With IUB jam and Coach on rainstick.
data.jamchartnote: Multi-layered creative journey w/ 2 distinct jams. 1st starts with an "IUB"/"I is" vocalization & high energy jam. 2nd jam contains chaotic 2-guitar attack, Creatures-like groove &  another shredding peak. Slows down for a landing into Danger Zone.

Double guitar dancefest until jam shifts blissfully with around 4 minutes to go. Jam doesn’t necessarily slow down (if anything Ben pushes) but Peter shifts to keys and jam finds a melodic space to breathe and grow beautifully.
Another great high energy and unwavering 2019 jam. Peaks wonderfully before sliding into Doc Brown.
Typical rocking Creatures jam until 15th minute where we see an early example of how they can devolve it blissfully. Gorgeous Rick soloing and finish.
Great versatility found in the 2nd jam, where band brings jam up and down (centered around finding Pete a little space to shine on keys). Smooth transition to Electric Avenue.

Special jam that travels to a spacey, beautiful, patient place. Trevor locks into a gorgeous bass line while Pete plays melodic and wistful piano and Rick builds a soaring, heart-wrenching guitar solo. The bass line outros this masterpiece.
One of the best openers you will hear. Extended beautiful Reba-like intro jam.

Tightly played song proper drops right into  into a tension filled, staccato jam. Out of the tension, the band finds a glory-rock chord progression that doesn’t quit. After a glorious peak, a false ending leads to a bonus dark-minor jam.
Enjoyable, Secret Agent Man-like groove.
Fiery, high energy version with a spectacular, triumphant peak. Definition of a Type 1 heater.
One of the finest versions ever played. Incredible and soaring Rick.

data.footnote: Included "Take A Lap" and "Coach on Rainstick" bingo balls. Each band member and Coach took a lap around the barn.
data.jamchartnote: A first jam that stays within bounds but explodes with the power of the sun leads into a second jam where the band members each have to "Take a Lap". Peter steps out early with aggressive guitar riffing as Rick and the drums lock in on each other as the music takes on a runaway freight train vibe. When Spuds finally takes his turn, Jeff picks up the beat out of the fragmented space and crafts an airy, major-key jam. Coach hops on rainstick and Rick adds some vocalizing as it slowly and patiently winds down.

data.footnote: FTP. Mystery Song #1. Included "15 Minute Jam" bingo ball.
data.jamchartnote: Mystery Ball #1 for Bingo Tour N1 resulted in what might be considered one of their most epic FTP jams ever due to +15 minute jam bingo ball pulled as song ended. Funky groovy start that turns melodic and once Ben picks up the pace, Rick rips one of his patented, god-like shred peaks.

data.footnote: "Rotation Jam" bingo ball. With Rick on drums, Peter on bass, Spuds on percussion, Trevor on guitar, and Jeff on keys.
data.jamchartnote: Rick on drums, Peter on bass, Jeff on keys, Trevor on guitar, Spuds on percussion. Loads of fun.
Nonstop triumph. Must-hear.

data.footnote: "No Drums" bingo ball. Rick, Peter, and Trevor only.
data.jamchartnote: Sticks to a really pleasant major-key vibe throughout. Spuds and Jeff rejoin the band midway through and add to the joy. Melts away > to "Factory Fiction" bustout.
The king of "Factory Fiction". Rick leads off with filthy envelope filter and delay work. The band then moves through some stop/start play before executing a massive build to a scorching peak.
Interesting Rick from the beginning, lots of whammy octave-up usage. Phenomenal -> to "Creatures".
-> in from "Hot Tea". Peppy version that hits nice two-chord jam on the outro before seamlessly returning to "Tea".
End of a fantastic "Hot Teatures" sandwich.
The Ben Atkind show. Absolutely monstrous performance on the drums as Rick and Peter dig in on some fast-paced riffs over top.

Two main segments to this monster. Rick initially crafts a soaring hose motif as he and Peter really lock in on the dual guitars. As the first peak fades away, we are treated to a flamethrower of a ripping jam, going around for more and more builds before finally screaming into the finish. Winner of JOTY 2020.
The legendary HOSEWOOD. Must-hear.
Tender and gorgeous play. Really beautiful stuff.
Encore/Final Song of an incredible show, this is one of the happiest, most melodic, pleasing jams you will hear before a fiery, passionate finish.
First section of the jam rages along with Peter's new clav. Peak dies away as Grippo hops on stage and he and Rick start trading licks like old friends. The stuff sit-in dreams are made of.
data.venuename: Higher Ground Drive-In at the Essex Junction Exposition Center

data.jamchartnote: Standard groove in the second jam is accentuated by Peter's clav work.
data.venuename: Higher Ground Drive-In at the Essex Junction Exposition Center

data.footnote: Walter Murphy. With Dave Grippo on saxophone.
data.jamchartnote: Saxophone on this. Yes please.
data.venuename: Higher Ground Drive-In at the Essex Junction Exposition Center

data.jamchartnote: Grippo adds beautifully to the Type I section of the jam. Out of the space, Spuds kicks into a funk groove and the band dives headfirst into a space highly reminiscent of Herbie Hancock. Rick and Grippo trade licks off each other like old friends while Peter saws away at grimy rhythm guitar. Builds in this zone for a while and is a must-hear piece of improv.
data.venuename: Higher Ground Drive-In at the Essex Junction Exposition Center

data.jamchartnote: The big Grippo finale. *chef's kiss*
data.venuename: Higher Ground Drive-In at the Essex Junction Exposition Center

data.jamchartnote: Peter continues to demonstrate the significance of his clav on this jam. Jaw-dropping funk.

Shifting between different styles to start, Rick finds a repeating melodic riff he comes back to on multiple occasion while Ben ecstatically and ferociously drives jam towards its powerful conclusion.
A month before "Empress" would be debuted with Goose, the band finds that progression in the midst of this show-closing "Lee" and hits several strong peaks in that vein.
Peter really simmers on this jam. Groovy and dark-tinged.
Rick needs to tune on the intro, so we get some extra vamping. Jam builds into spacey mode and gets into a great -> to "Doc Brown".
Hints at dark themes that will come to fruition in 2021 and 2022, includes Peter siren synth loops.
Crunchy clav funk and breakdowns make for a strong debut.
Gets into some real dark themes. Unfinished and a great -> to "Doobie Song".
Most notable for the Goedde laser show. Video is available on the band's YouTube.
Switches gears almost immediately with Spuds rocking the ride cymbal. Nonstop high-octane hose with "Hot Tea" teases from Rick.
Rick tears up the first jam while Spuds and Jeff absolutely dominate the second. One of the band's best segues ever goes perfectly -> to "Jive Lee".
data.venuename: Spirit of the Suwannee Music Park

data.jamchartnote: First really exploratory jam of 2021 and it hints at the development of the "Ted" motif that will be come prevalent throughout the year. Back half is some great dual-guitar funk that eventually bleeds into an explosive "Bob Don."
Dissolves into darker Ted motif before smoothly transitioning, unfinished, -> to "Spirit of the Dark Horse" bustout.
Rick puts his new wah pedal through its paces. Serious tension.

First "Creatures" jam ever with Peter on keys and he more than delivers. Steps up on Vintage Vibe and grooves along until Rick takes over in what will be the new standard jam for the song. Jam dissolves into rhythm-section-driven Ted space at the back end before landing smoothly in a perfectly-placed "Your Ocean." Absolute must-hear and a pivotal moment for the evolution of Goose jams.
While the set opening "Creatures" showcases the band's newer jamming style, this Tumble revisits their tried-and-true groove/peak method. Amazing version.
Taken at a slower pace than usual and hits a cool groove in the middle with great synth work from Peter.

data.footnote: With Rick on acoustic guitar and a mid-jam switch to electric.
data.jamchartnote: Starts acoustic and turns electric for the jam. Doesn't quite top Hosewood, but it's close.
Improvisational version that gets a bit dissonant before a perfect -> to "Jive II" to complete the first-ever performance of the full triptych.
-> in from "Jive Lee". One of two versions to date with the bonus "third jam", which hits on some major-key themes and peaks well before fading to "Wysteria Lane".
Gets a lot done in its relatively short runtime though its potential could have been explored more. Followed by the debut of Ted Tapes cut "Moby".
Thrilling, rockstar finish and start of a very cool "Madhuvan" > "Dark Horse" > "Madhuvan" sandwich.
One of the best versions ever - the jam is like a drive with the top down on a summer afternoon. Pure joy.
Lots of patience in this one.
Gets funkier than most versions and closes nicely with "Loose Ends".
Second version and most recent (to date) with "third jam". While the Caverns' version focused on bliss, this goes straight funk with standout clav from Peter.
Secret Agent Madhuvan.
Greg Knight rips up some serious freestyle and the band gets a little bit atypical with the "E or A?" groove after his departure.
Big-ticket song performance at a homecoming show for the band.
Gets more done than most 15-minute first set versions. Highlight of an otherwise unremarkable show.

One of Goose's best jams ever. Starts with a Ted space and gradually moves through many different themes, both beautiful and rocking. Peaks MASSIVELY and - without missing a beat or even taking a moment to bask in the glory - segues -> to an equally good (if not better) "Echo of a Rose." Winner of JOTY 2021.
-> from the legendary Perry "A Western Sun". Second jam is an absolutely incredible slow-build. Incredible contributions from all five members - do NOT miss!
Only version to date with "(7hunder)" ending.

Breaks out of "Empress" proper into a driving groove. Peter hits the clav and things go to another level before Rick grabs hold and REALLY pours on the gas. Absolutely insane jam and peak before they take their time with the outro progression.
Powerful version with great guitar interplay between Rick and Peter.
Propulsive (and long) Peter-led jam that gets into a unique "slow" ending for the only time to date.

June 2021's other mammoth "Arcadia" begins with a quick bathroom break from Rick as the jam starts. Picks up speed into a high-octane series of peaks before smashing down into the first performance of the "slow" ending. Never returns to the full peak but finishes beautifully.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With I Can't Turn You Loose teases.
data.jamchartnote: Retains a blissful sentiment throughout. Great envelope filter work from Rick in the second jam.
Angular and staccato jamming. Continues "Rosewood"'s strong 2021.

In honour of Jeff's 1-year anniversary in the band, he gets to sing before the second-ever "Cleveland" dives headlong into a deep and funky jam that rides to a great peak to close the first set of this legendary Legend Valley show.
Soaring and beautiful, as "Elmeg" is wont to do.

The second half of the sandwich, the "Madhuvan" jam emerges dissonantly from the "Moby" ending and is 13 minutes of a runaway freight train. Rick and Peter especially shine with their insane duelling guitar work. Must-hear.
An especially amazing and emotional Rick solo begins this encore version and is elevated by perfectly placed siren synths from Peter.
Moves and builds upon a melodic riff for several minutes to a soaring peak like none I’ve heard, and then settles beautifully.
Improvisational version that departs the typical jam.
First ever "Slow Ready" to continue the arpeggiator jam - Peter crafts a laid-back groove that the band sits in for a while before a perfect -> to "Drive".
-> from "Slow Ready". Continues the perfect flow of this set with a great jam before leading -> into "Can't Get You Outta My Head" and "Mais Que Nada".
Hornsby gets taken into outer space atop atmospheric guitar and heavy Vintage Vibe from Peter. An absolute must-hear piece of music.
Gets into a nice plinko jam toward the end.
In the all-time pantheon of Goose jams. First jam rages into a synth-dominated second. Montana delivers.
Torrin Daniels of Kitchen Dwellers on banjo.
Jam settles into a driving two-guitar groove. Peter finds the Magic School Bus theme and they riff on it for a few minutes before a phenomenal -> to "Echo of a Rose".
Serious gas in this shorter version with a fiery vocal-infused ending.
SUPER-extended intro jam. Great guitar interplay.

Pete continuously shifts the jamming style on the keys from a 4-note repeating funk to slowed down patience back to melodic joy and ending in a gorgeous repeating hook before jam melts away. Band follows suit each time in a short but pretty example of great improv jamming on a cover.
data.venuename: Sculpture Park at Denver Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Fairly standard two-guitar rocking which slows down and gets into darker jamming at the end, sliding -> into "Creatures."
data.venuename: Sculpture Park at Denver Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Rick at his absolute best. If you're looking for an example of Rick taking a jam by the balls, look no further than the last 4 minutes of this jam.
data.venuename: Sculpture Park at Denver Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Bright and major key play peaks and transitions into grimy clav funk with heavy "Loose Ends" teasing.
Peter shines on Vintage Vibe during the second jam.
Floating melodic start that builds into a smoke show. Finish starts as pretty major key and then devolves into nastiness.
Standard ripping first jam that turns into almost a marching plinko jam before pretty resolution and ending.
Lots of stop/start fun.
Absolute rhythm guitar CLINIC from Peter.
Former Goose member Chris "Doc" Enright adds some funky Vintage Vibe to the song as well as an awesome synth solo. Top-tier version.

data.footnote: With Matt Campbell on keys and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: Significant rendition with Matt Campbell on keys and vocals.

Multifaceted festival "Flee." Band breaks into percussive space as Peter uses his backlined Rhodes for some Manzarek-like playing. A peak leads to some clav and organ funk that eventually blitzes into the finish. Keyboard showcase.
STRONG Rick and hints at the darkness.

Peter shifts the mode of this jam when he switches to dampened clav and then vibraphone piano. A percussive groove emerges and Rick pulls out a blissful progression not unlike an "Arcadia" jam. HUGE peaking ensues before a perfect ending.
Laid-back jam with serious "Welcome to Delta" hints from Peter. Foreshadows where the song will go in 2022.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. Played with the original "fast" ending.
data.jamchartnote: Gradually picks up steam throughout thanks to incredible playing from Rick and insistent drumming from Spuds. Crashes into the ending at such a speed that they swap in the "fast" instrumental ending instead of singing the chorus.
Nicely extended show-opening version.
Notable mostly for the amazing segue -> to "Jive I".
SPACE. TED.
High-concept crescendoing transcendence built around a lilting melody make for a soul-expanding 2nd jam.
Peter has a BLAST with his new wireless guitar setup - bouncing all around the stage while vamping off Rick throughout the long second jam.

Peter leans into the envelope filter on his guitar as the band luxuriates in an incredible funk zone for several minutes early on. Making a major-key push from there, Rick confidently leads several huge builds that come together for a massive final peak. Outstanding version.

data.footnote: With Within You Without You tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Standard "Arcadia" fare for the majority, but the final section dives into a menacing and extended build, a great foreshadow to the Winter 2022 style of jamming.
Thrashy, dark, metal-adjacent. Hell yes.
Super funky jam with great clav, a solid peak, and even better Trevor.
Peter extends the outro and the band settles into a nice low-key groove for a bit before sliding seamlessly -> to "Arcadia".
Inspiring, get-your-ass-out-bed-and-do-something-with-your-life first jam, followed by groove dance party and epic re-build to glory.

First version with the drum break after the first chorus. The band takes the jam with ferocity, building in a linear fashion yet engaging in amazing interplay on the way to several peaks. Crashes back into the ending and Spuds plays us into the opening of "Drive" in lieu of a second jam.

Eschews the first jam and goes right into the driving second after the "whoa" section. Immedate and FURIOUS dual-guitar attack. Peter goes ham on envelope filter early on before Rick takes control and shreds.

Typical groove fest that settles down before incredible interplay between Rick and Peter. Driving bass and pulsating drumming and percussion pick jam back up. Peter then starts sirens and comes in hot before letting Ben close out with some very cool soloing.

data.footnote: The Trammps. With River Lullaby teases.
data.jamchartnote: Clav party jam.
Jam begins with a descending progression not unlike a "Mind Left Body". Really strong version.

Laid-back guitar churn for the first half makes a major modulation along with Peter's switch to Vibe. A pleasant and driving motif emerges thanks to propulsive drumming from Spuds and Jeff for the final minutes as Peter leads the way.
REALLY spacey jam develops out of this cover. Surprising jam vehicle.
Joyous, momentous build (you’ll know when it’s happening, impossible not to smile during it) that devolves into dark unregulated chaos before rising back in full fury finish.
First jam gets chunky thanks to Spuds and the clav. Peter rips up the second jam on piano before fading nicely > to "No Rain".
Rick and Peter REALLY extend the intro with some solo-trading, Jeb gets "they're all bongos" treatment, and the whole jam just RAGES. Incredible version.

30-minute version stays relatively close to home until around 19 minutes, when it shifts to a bright and major key. This vibe gradually picks up steam before peaking again and transitioning > to "Caution".
First jammed version in a while goes for it and reaches an awesome major-key peak before slamming -> to the ending of "Time to Flee".
Fall '21 was a great time for "Dragonfly" - emerges perfectly out of "Spirit of the Dark Horse" to close the set.
First version with the full Peter organ solo. Soars to the heavens.
The first "With" and perhaps the best, the contemplative jam gains in energy before exploding into the final chorus of "All I Need".
Standard jam fades into a GORGEOUS motif. You may not realize it initially, but it becomes clear that the segue -> to "Crosseyed and Painless" is imminent.
All-around balls-to-the-walls energy. Rick absolutely torches Kansas City while Spuds spurs him on. Expressive vocal ending.
Funky jam develops with a great -> to "Butter Rum".
Great -> from "I'm A Believer". Spuds keeps the backbeat vibe going throughout the song before an extended jam emerges.
Heavy and psychedelic vibe in the latter half with "Mad World" teases - the band opts to leave "Tea" unfinished and -> to a poppy duo of "Dancing in the Moonlight" and "Shama Lama Ding Dong".
Shorter version but brimming with passion throughout. Gorgeous cool down mid-jam that rises patiently and blissfully. True glory hose finish before returning to song ending.
Swirling, chaotic, yet in control. Slight cool down before swirl picks back up amid organ-driven finish.
Melodic jamming slowly swelling particularly as Pete ramps up on second guitar. Seemingly coming to a grand finish, they take a lovely quieter approach for the final four minutes.
Much like the Terminal 5 "Look Out Cleveland", the Mission "Rockdale" just builds into this intense "Arcadia"-like jam and peaks spectacularly.
Vibey "Tumble" gets a jam for the first time, gradually picking up speed until a high-speed peak closes it out.

Show opener for a fan favorite show, jam starts in earnest at the 10:30 mark and stays within a pretty standard rocking tempo throughout. Ripping final peak and cool final minute cooldown into "Travelers."

The Mission Arcadia: After funky start, band collectively builds into one of Goose’s most blissful & beautiful jams ever. After return to song ending (watch video for “THE LOOK”), Denver is obliterated by one of their most majestic peaks in history.
Melodic, funky, energy building that transitions into "Drive." Longest "Sea" to date and another crowd pleaser from a great couple of shows from the Mission.

Fitting encore for the final show in an incredible Fall ‘21 tour. Riffing around the FF song at start of jam, then dark "Crazy Train" CCP style jamming before bringing the tour home in an enthusiastic fashion.

Soak in this Flee as a peaceful gentleness settles in to start. Gorgeous keys by Peter and Rick mimics the style. Like a flowing wave, Trevor and percussion begin increasing tempo and volume as band rises magically only to settle back down in the earlier quiet style, then build back to a fiery finish.
Second-ever "Bob Don With". Really nice contemplative jam.
Melodious and smooth, driven by Peter's grooves.

Show opener for NYE ‘21, starting as a type 1 rocker with melodic playing by Rick and Trevor and Peter laying some lovely supporting guitar effects. Cooldown ensues until drumming intensifies and band power towards the finish.
Peter goes wild on synth during the intro.
Extended intro and creative groove fest.

data.footnote: With Bingo Tour Theme and Mad World teases.
data.jamchartnote: Jam takes direction from Pete’s piano, even letting him take a lovely solo, before band comes back in building to a gorgeous, soaring peak. Melts away blissfully before great "Tumble".

Tour de force by Pete and Trevor. They seamlessly lead the band from funk, to space rock, to an ultimately glorious resolution. Ben and Jeff really kick it in and for the last 7 min it’s an all out disco-funk party. Melts into evil dissonant space.
Strong debut with propulsive drums and piano.
Rick shines in this outside-the-box version.
Debut version is amazing with the loooooong synth build. Groovy second half of the jam.
Gets into a super psychedelic zone and sandwiches in an amazing "Tomorrow Never Knows" with smooth segues on either side.
Soaring, beautiful peak. Peter is especially fond of this version.

data.footnote: With Jive II and Don't Do It teases.
data.jamchartnote: Fairly standard minor-key groove that downshifts into a cool half-time segment with "Jive II" and "Don't Do It" teasing. Returns home for a strong finish.
Technical difficulties lead to an extended ending jam that segues nicely -> to "Writing A Novel".

Melodic soaring jam gives way to synthy darkness/heavy metal thrashing (begins ~10:45). Incredibly composed & patient swelling of dark jam before massive tension releases. One of Goose’s most significant jams signalling never-before-seen jamming style.
The band shows remarkable restraint and patience and really take their time developing the themes and reaching the peak.
More early 2022 dual-guitar insanity. Really exploratory and excellent version.

Show opens with Echo but comes back to it a 2nd time. 2nd Echo starts with glory rock and then synthy haunting bring down at 10 minutes, similar to 3/4 Pancakes though more extended & then with an incredibly cool & patient march to finish.
Ripping early peak followed by lovely melodic repeating dancing groove. Last 4 minutes find a quick slowdown and shift to more traditional rocking finish.
THE CHURN.
Gold standard for blissful early jamming section with Pete's gorgeous keys and an all-time Rick solo. Standard but dance-filled groove in second half.
More propulsive arrangement than later versions.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Ghostbusters Rap teases.
data.jamchartnote: Harkens back to the big 2019 versions with 2022 maturity. Short but beautifully melodic first jam, ripping dancefest to start second jam that almost comes to a complete halt before gradually building back up to a gorgeous groove and -> to "Doc Brown".
2022 Elizabeth clav funk that rocks on and slides -> perfectly into "Moby".
Perfect pairing with "Dragonfly" for half an hour of unadulterated, raging Goose.

Starts with bliss mode but shifts gears around 11:00. Rick pushes into staccato motif and Peter hammers the Vintage Vibe as swirling siren synth swells dominate. Evil arrives and the band pounds away at a roaring wave of a peak before closing with bliss.

data.footnote: Fast version. With Flodown tease from Spuds.
data.jamchartnote: Joyous and major-key playing dominate this standout version.
Cool arrangement only played twice in Winter 2022. Gets into a great spacey jam.
Opening version continues the churn theme from 2/3's version and raises.
Wide open 2nd jam noodles pensively but prettily for about 10 mins before Pete and Trevor elevate a big rave up conclusion.
27 min multi-part monster Arrow. Tweekz/Spuds-led space groove vibe -> Peter wah guitar party over a steady rhythmic gallop -> brief foray into dark jamming -> unique/pretty minor key peak.
Trevor leads off with a stanky slap solo. Really simmers and churns below the surface as the nastiness and tension build to a frenzied peak. Really strong version.
Delta jam bounces along to a great peak before Rick pops a string and Peter leads the rest of the band into a spooky and haunting motif that acts as the intro to "Dr. Darkness".
Unique version of Pancakes that finds a much more gentle, restrained  jam mid-way, before catching an energetic wave with 5 minutes to go in a rousing finish.
Nasty and crunchy.
Major-key happiness.

That thunder Seger was waiting on has finally arrived and it is Tweekz. Out of the ashes of this foundation shaking polyrhythmic cacophony emerges your new avian overlord, a screaming terrible phoenix sent to punish us all, the mighty Pittsbird.
Molten hot lava jam.
At the time of its debut, nobody had heard "Hungersite" before and it immediately establishes itself as a jam vehicle. Great rocking motif before the segue into the live debut of "Dripfield".
All about the drums. Debut version stays within the song but MAN is it good.

Seems to be heading in a fairly standard direction but a subtle shift leads the band into dark territory. Peter lays down some low textures on Vibe as Rick shreds the minor-key. Explosive ending and return to song proper.

Jam begins by hitting into a "Dripfield"-like theme that throws us into driving darkness. Space is whipped up as the motif reaches its apex. We come down on the other side with a classic rock-feeling jam that just grooves and rages to the end.

data.footnote: With I Wish teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: As if 3/1's second set wasn't good enough already, the band drops a 20-minute "Pancakes" to close it out. Hard-charging and funky, this doesn't hit much new territory but is just such an excellent groove. Rick closes it out with perfectly placed "I Wish" teases.
The band is in no hurry and really explores every inch of the Delta motif before descending into evil space, setting up "Dr. Darkness".

Typically blissful first jam opts to go dark instead. Twisted riffs from Rick bring it to a boil before crashing into the final chorus. Short second jam sees Peter taking lead on organ before an almost three-minute slow-burn segue -> to "Arrow".
Peter steps out first on Vintage Vibe and then clav at the beginning of the jam. Post-peak, it downshifts into a mellow groove that eventually -> to "Pumped Up Kicks".
Stank-face-inducing funk.
Peter extends the arpeggiator and the band settles into a fantastic and psychedelic groove that sits for a while before Rick initiates a patient and perfect -> to "Hot Tea".

-> in from a super-extended "Slow Ready". Peter turns the arpeggiator back on during the "Tea" jam for a really unique take that also includes a nice tease of the Ted Tape track "Europa" from Rick. Well worth a listen.

Experimental adventurous inter-dimensional. Rocking initial jam leads to devastating & incredible haunting section at ~14:00. Trev powers them out of it & they begin climb to the top of Rock & Roll mountain. Epic peak & perfect return to song ending.

This sludge-y riff rock monster of a Rockdale is the first truly extended venture for the song and features elements of That's All (Genesis), Peter absolutely wailing on clav & vibes, and a Dragonfly-esque progression to bring it all home.
Melts into nothingness before before building back into seemingly everything in a spectacular white-knuckle peak then gorgeously -> "Rosewood Heart".
This first jam peaks so insanely hard, Rick is in full god mode. Excellent second jam akin to "speed jazz" circa Summer '93 Phish and -> "Echo of a Rose" ending.
Trevor leads the band into a jam that's almost like Phish's "Wolfman's Brother".

July 1999. Jetta Factory. Guangzhou, CN. In a syncopated rhythmic dance the Furbys whir & clink down the assembly line. A sudden burst of deafening light incinerates workers as the Phoenix apparates, providing a new directive. Tiger Electronics source code overwritten w/ dark sentience. Beaks accented w/ razor blades. Eyes w/ lasers. Fur w/ mecha scales. Wings snap into place. With cries of mangled Furbish, the nightmare creatures swarm like bats through the window above to carry out their terrible mission.
Melodic major key goodness through. Similar feel and vibes as the Mission Arcadia (perhaps highlighted by Peter’s keys), with uplifting beautiful finish.
The younger sibling of 1/30 and 3/1. Hits on dark themes but doesn't explore them to the same extent as the other two Winter 2022 behemoth "Wysteria".
Gold standard for blissful early jamming section with Pete's gorgeous keys and an all-time Rick solo. Standard but dance-filled groove in second half.

data.footnote: With Echo of a Rose jam.
data.jamchartnote: 38 minute two part monster. First 23 minutes highlight Goose’s ability to drive their jams in different directions. Second begins with a clear shift into Echo, resulting in an Echo jam and finishing into an epic raging peak.
Gets a second outro jam for the first time ever. Gorgeous major-key playing.
Peter plays with the reverb on the organ early on in the jam for a haunting vibe.

data.footnote: With Oh Yeah quote from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Extended and funky groove. No one band member is really soloing, which lends a unique and cool quality to it.
Long show-opening version explores some interesting themes. Peter adds some incredible textures including some "Creatures" teases. Smooth -> to "Writing a Novel".

Jam flows magically with so much purpose, from methodical funk to beautiful blissful bring down to glorious climbing march to experimenting with darkness to rocking finish. Great improv with diverse jamming themes.
Disco dance party. Unfinished.
The usual Vibe jam gets funkier. Peter hits the clav and the band blasts their way perfectly -> into a huge "Use Me" bustout.
Standard "Drip" jam at first gives way to a fast-paced "Shama"-like bliss jam. Excellent high-octane peak before finishing the song.
Relentless and long first jam seamlessly transitions between major and minor key. Short second jam sees Peter doing some sparse organ leading before landing in "California Magic".
Ultra-funky molasses jamming. Trevor puts on a clinic concocting murderous bass lines while Rick lets his inner SRV come out to play, absolutely scorching blues soloing.

Typically beautiful "Sea" jam fragments into intense, evil noises, making you grab your blanket for dear life as Peter cackles among looping marimba arpeggiators, Rick effects, and other general madness. Would be right at home as a "Dr. D" intro but resolves instead into a fantastic "Factory Fiction" set closer.
Classic > from "Jive I." Jam immediately takes a darker turn behind Peter’s Nord synth and settles into a vibey groove. Unique version.

On this Bird's lucky voyage #7 we become hypnotized by cyclical dizzying flight patterns while a menacing undercurrent of fuzzed out Fuck Buttons-esque synth washes and coordinated sonic booms slowly cracks open a glowing fissure in the Earth, the triumphant cries of the Ashebird grow ever murderous and it goes in for the kill, ripping our face clean off our head and sending us plummeting to our molten doom.

The name of the game is efficiency. Trevor plows forward into the minor key out of his solo and the drummers develop a deep pocket. Peter hits the clav and Rick hangs back for a while to let him rip before taking the reins himself. Goes straight for the jugular and doesn't let up for a second.
After standard rocking, band brings jam down with six minutes to go and proceeds to build up melodically and magically.

data.footnote: With Welcome to Delta jam and Atlas Dogs teases.
data.jamchartnote: Pokes and prods at the edges of the "Delta" jam before finally breaking into a warm major-key motif that winds up back in the Indie-Groove "Atlas Dogs" progression. Great early summer evening jam.

Grooving jam until switch to 2-guitars & there is a melodic march up to a lovely peak. Spacey synthy outro jam turns into 2nd jam with funk-filled finish. Listen for the genesis of the "Thatch" opening lick five months before the song's debut.
Beautiful soaring majestic finish to another strong version of "Lee" in 2022.

Often overlooked because of the all-time Raleigh version a week later, don’t sleep on this version. Flowing, rich, layered. Beautiful mid-jam cooldown as Rick patiently picks the perfect time to rise from it and solo beautifully.
Builds up an impressive head of steam with aggressive Nord work from Peter before cooling and smoothly transitioning -> to "Into the Myst."
Peter hits the keys early on in this standout "Half Step," working the Vintage Vibe and Nord synth to create a spacey vibe that the band feeds off of.

6 minutes of heaven. After a great opening rocking jam, at 18:47 Peter finds a gorgeous 4-note theme that the band latches onto and builds around in the most chilling and awe-inspiring way. One of the most beautiful sections of any Goose jam ever.

This truly elite “All I Need” is dark Goose jamming at its finest. Trevor-forward full band interplay with Spuds mimicking a violent half-speed thrash metal death march creates space for Rick to swirl brain-breaking minor-key runs over a bed of extra-terrestrial synths. If aliens ever attack, they’ll come blaring a six-minute loop of this jam on repeat from their flying saucer Alpines. The accidental second jam features some fine clav-work from Peter and an extended moody intro to “Nights in White Satin”.
Debut includes almost three minutes of synth intro from Peter and a long and groovy jam that stays within the typical groove.
Absolutely crushing encore version to close out Legend Valley takes a turn for the bombastic with a "Factory Fiction" ending jam in place of the usual "Rockdale" peak.

Multi-section masterpiece taking a journey through time & space. After breakdown/opening jam, band builds up to evil psychotic heavy metal shredding. Pete then switches to keys, Jeff adds chimes & Rick performs one of his most beautiful solos ever. Winner of JOTY 2022.

The song's 2022 evolution really begins here as the band opts to jam out of Rick's solo section. Great keys work from Peter eventually morphs into a layered motif with excellent use of space by Peter on organ while Rick unleashes some dark-ish soloing. Under-the-radar yet excellent jam.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: The riff that forever changed the future of Rock & Roll. Goose’s incredible first song/jam ft Trey Anastasio w/ beautiful double guitar intro & Trey hits THAT MOMENT. Great repeating hook at end that allows Trey to shred the final jam peak.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: The Original Artreydia. Lovely guitar interplay & Trey song phrasing shifts to blissful magic as Peter switches to piano. Free-like riffing leads to Trey nailing the peak & handing the torch to Rick to close it out. Euphoric moment in Goose history.
Rick and Trey once again shine with their immediate guitar chemistry, harmonizing lick after lick and closing out the historic sit-in set with a boom.

Peter expertly controls the mood on this festival highlight encore, moving the jam sections along from clav, to vibraphone/piano, to an unconventional and experimental arpeggiator transition into the ending breakdown.

Strong dual guitar attacking jam changes dramatically and beautifully as Pete shifts to synth effects around 18:45, creating a space groove and allowing Trevor and Ben to shine. Pete goes to keys a few minutes later as band builds up to a rocking finish.
Went Gin-like Magic. One of the happiest jams you’ll hear emerges in the last 6 minutes. Rick finds a gorgeous hook and band builds until they find collective joyful hose.

Double guitar rock with energetic, ripping initial 11 minutes. Jam then begins to get weird and devolve into dark space. Manic alien-style effects develop and haunting synths surround a slow, patient march to the finish.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Sinnerman teases.
data.jamchartnote: 36 min monster throws down. Very short first jam (ends at 9:15) leads to their longest second jam ever. Very patient jams with short melodic sections intertwined with spacey synths. Jam never quite reaches heights of other AINs but quite the journey.

Hauntingly beautiful jam finds potential trouble as Rick breaks a string (16:45ish). Instead Peter synths & Trevor bass fill the void powerfully allowing Rick to rejoin (18:30) transforming the jam into a slow, evil abduction of the Chrysalis crowd.
Last 5 minutes are spectacular, arena-ready rocking. They catch a lightning in a bottle theme here and jam the hell out of it to a ripping, frenzied peak.

Gorgeous early jam followed by groovy dance-funk. Right before 13 mins, band slows groove & locks in patiently. Tumble tease @ 17:40 creates driving jam leading to collective repeating theme. Band eggs on crowd Woos & melts jam away.

Absolute perfect 2-guitar goose with both guitarists feeling it and toggling seamlessly between dark, penetrating  and celebratory, frolicking jams and back again! It was a special jam where the crowd could sense greatness the moment they veered away from the song!
2nd phenomenal EoA in the span of a week. Early funk-fest opens up finding more experimentation between the melodic, tension-filled madness and heart-pumping Trevor bass.

Percussion-driven glory seems to end after a soaring peak in the 14th minute only to rise from the ashes blissfully. Magical tear-jerking beauty with some of Trevor and Rick's most beautiful playing ends the jam.
Kylie in s2 closer slot does what you might expect. Dark house music builds in intensity as Ben increases the pace. Dissolves into another deep synth wash across encore break and -> "Hot Tea".
data.songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head

data.jamchartnote: Ragecadia. Very atypical version where Ben goes double time with around 5 minutes to go and band takes off at blistering pace. No build up, no bliss, no slow ending. Just pure raging fire.
Typical rocking relentlessness gives way to a melodic almost calypso-like, lighter sound in the 14th minute. Blissful magic grows with gorgeous stop/start jamming and a beautiful peak.

Three part incredible jam: ~5 min bliss jam with glory peak > ~6 min epic funky cool down jam that you think is leading to end but instead builds back up to > ~6 min rock/party/dance fest & huge peak.
First-ever unfinished Pancakes. Rick finds a psychedelic and spacey riff around the 11-minute mark and the band develops that excellently for the remainder of the jam.
Never dull runaway freight train of a version. Just when you think it has peaked and is ending, it finds yet another level of energy and intensity.
"Thriller"-style build (also sharing strong similarities with the 8/17 Dillon "Borne" build).

Band finds a very cool theme they build around and seem ready to wind down before Big T says NO (~17:40) and re-ignites the jam. Rick latches onto Trevor’s new theme, combining with old theme, and drives to a rocking finish.
data.venuename: Arvest Bank Theater at the Midland

data.jamchartnote: Multi-section madness. Double guitar funk battle, amazing cool down showing tremendous patience and then wonderful percussion-powered buildup to more gorgeous feel good, glory jamming.
Great tension build and release leading to a spicier jam and peak.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Trey Anastasio on guitar.
data.jamchartnote: 1st sit-in of Taboose 2022 & it’s a monster. From the get-go, Trey perfectly integrates finding melodic hooks, syncing up with Ben & Trevor to drive them towards a rocking peak, funks it up Pete’s clav & then takes charge on an epic Evil jam.
Briskly tempo'd jam sets off with purpose and has some great layering of textures by Peter. Floats perfectly into the intro to "Echo."
Trey Anastasio sit-in. Shorter version for the year but contains absolutely gorgeous double-guitar interplay and bliss peak.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: Artreydia Take 2 leads to more pronounced dual guitar interplay/confidence. Jam gets to the point faster than the first version yet still contains much of the same beauty.

data.footnote: Fat Freddy's Drop. With Natalie Cressman on trombone, Jennifer Hartswick on trumpet, and James Casey on saxophone.
data.jamchartnote: TAB horns (Jen Hartswick, Natalie Cressman, James Casey) join in on a version that Peter mentions they always wished they could play with horns. Epic back and forth battle between James on sax and Rick on guitar highlights this very fun jam.
Trey Anastasio sits in for a very surprising and unique version of "FF."

Peter begins the jam with searing synth textures from his Nord Lead before switching to Vibe as a more melodic theme takes shape. The band fully explores this before bringing it home with a typically raging ending.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: Donning cap, goggles, & scarf you rev your doghouse engine and take to the sky, faithful yellow co-pilot at your side. Engaging The Big Red Baron you move into a graceful aerial dance, as many shots dodged as fired. With the Baron finally in your cross-hairs, a lurch & deafening BANG before you pull the trigger. Drat! What’s this? Woodstock is flying toward the Baron, looking orange and shifting redder. Sabotage! Betrayal! Your foes heckle you as your ruined engine sputters and you glide downward, defeated.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: This Old Trey sings backups & takes a solo during the song before immersing into another multi-section Taboose 2022 jam. Gorgeous bliss>rocking peaks>diving into the weird unknown in another great example of how locked in they all were this tour.

Peter lays down a bed of Prophet synth as Rick steers the jam into three-chord bliss. Hearkening back to the 10/1 "Ragecadia," Spuds pushes the tempo and the band blazes into a series of peaks before explosively returning home.
Set closer with Trey Anastasio. Shorter than the typical version but Spuds goes double time leading to rocking shredding finish.

The "Madhuvanastasio." Peter initiates a descending "Mind Left Body"-like progression on marimba piano as Rick and Trey dance around each other's melodies. Trey takes the lead on a major-key space as the jam picks up speed. Peaking well, it deconstructs into a darker build with great interplay from the two guitars and keys before exploding home.
Trey Anastasio sits in on a short but absolute rocking version of "Rockdale." One of the biggest peaks of the Trey sit-in jams.
El Trey the Red joins the band in the final show of the TABoose tour. Faster jam with Allman's style interplay.

data.footnote: With Trey Anastasio on guitar, James Casey on saxophone, Jennifer Hartswick on trumpet, and Natalie Cressman on trombone.
data.jamchartnote: Final Goose song of the TABoose tour features the only jam with both Trey and TAB horns.
Standard "Drive" fare until the last few minutes, where Rick and Peter dive headlong into evil shred as Spuds drums his ASS off.
Following a similar theme to 3/1/22's rager, Peter really shines on piano in this explosive version. Rick swaggers on some extra sustain at the end.

Airy groove develops early on when Peter makes the switch to keys. Trevor initiates a catchy hook and the band follows, developing the motif in an incredibly patient way. Jam pivots when Peter pulls the "Audience Group Hug" ball and Rick tears through a euphoric peak atop a wave of synthesizer. Fades into the perfect landing pad in "Moby."

Peter turns off the wah on the clav to add some extra grime as he leads Rick into heavy "Crazy Train" teasing - Rick then responds in kind by revving the jam up into high gear and hitting a phenomenal peak to close out the incredible set.

XL Flee jam moves into some very funky territory, with lots of percussive piano, wah-guitar, then screaming overdriven blues soloing, at points sounds like it could be -> "Thatch" but instead find it's way back to the triumphant Flee ending.
Absolute non-stop dance party. Jam may only contain one gear but it's one of the most fun, danceable jams you will hear from Goose.
First slow/OG Echo since Nov '21 explores a similar gorgeous melodic post-rock theme to the Legend Valley "Creatures" but w/o the same majesty of resolve.

data.footnote: Lyrics changed to reference the Fox Theatre.
data.jamchartnote: Goosemas funk is brought in early with Peter shifting across all his toys and Trevor reacting brilliantly. After Rick comes in and shreds slightly, jam slows down into a happier piano-driven blissful finish.

data.footnote: Talking Heads. With Axel F teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Very short yet beautiful intro jam. Axel Foley teases and shredding, fist-pumping dancefest that slows down slightly with Peter throwing everything at the jam (marimba, synths, keys) and Trevor’s bass driving jam forward.
This jam is a groove. Propelled early by Trevor, the majority of this jam is a mellow, calming vibe before it very sneakily increases tempo and intensity leading to a joyous conclusion.
Gorgeous almost 6-minute intro with beautiful Peter vibraphone before the song starts. With a full-on Heartbreaker jam.

Sandwiched in between two Madhuvans, this 80 seconds contains one of Rick's gnarliest guitar solos of all time. After an entire set of black and white aesthetics, the ALS was accompanied by an explosion of color (lights, balloons)

data.footnote: The Beatles. With Bob Weir on guitar and vocals.
data.jamchartnote: Bob Weir's sit-in sees "TMK" get taken for a much more spacey ride than we are used to with Goose. Very interesting listen.
Grows in intensity like many versions before it and slides nicely into a "Hollywood Nights" jam.
TREVOR BASS. That is all.
Rocking jam with lots of great Vibe and synth from Peter eventually disintegrates into a minute or so of percussive play before -> to "Kylie."
The rhythm section keeps the pace up while Peter lays down a bright progression. The band jams on a theme akin to "Love is a Battlefield" before transitioning neatly to "Electric Avenue."
Atypical arpeggiator starts off the first headlining performance of 2023. The band vibes and gets loose within the confines of the groove before finishing "Electric Avenue" from Okeechobee.

Right out of the gate, the band dives into some Winter '22-style dark jamming. Peter goes to a haunting upright piano tone as he and Rick lock in. Spuds shoots the improv into a swirling vortex that transitions cleanly into some bluesy rock at Rick's urging. Organ and guitar trade riffs before Rick steers the band into three-chord bliss. Trevor really steps out on the sustained full-band peak w/ envelope filter work as the joyous peak wraps back to "AIN" proper and a second jam fakeout into "Dr. D."

data.footnote: With Earthling or Alien? tease from Trevor.
data.jamchartnote: Extra-mustard version with a Trevor Bass solo.

data.footnote: With Jive II teases from Trevor.
data.jamchartnote: Boundary-pushing jam highlighted by Rick's dreamlike trills at 12:45 and Peter's synths at 14:58. Hazy ambient drift with no end goal, and no need for one - just totally locked in and thematic jamming: brilliant sign for the Cap & Spring Tour.

Fiery Type 1 jam breaks at 12:16 into open plane of space highlighted by Trevor Bass. A contemplative & melancholic jam emerges, bringing to mind Talk Talk and The Cure, centered around gorgeous leads from Rick & Peter before > to "Doobie."

All-time first jam that starts off with fiery Rick shredding and melts into one of the most beautiful sections of patient, double-guitar bliss you will hear. Second jam contains a funk party that ends with Loose Ends jamming.
Dark, eerie jamming (almost but not quite Crazy Train) that begins to speed up relentlessly, quiets down before the close and then returns to Rockdale out of a tension-filled frenzy.

data.footnote: With Pick Up The Pieces teases from Rick and Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Double guitar funk, effect-filled start that takes a melodic turn as Pete switches to keys. Very cool ending as Rick finds a repeating theme he toys around as the rest of the band builds around him.
Percussive and taut jamming around the Rosewood theme leads to a hypnotic jamming segment on the backhalf when the rythm section hooks up with Rick & Peter channeling Neu! & Kraftwerk.
Haunting yet patient dark opening jam takes off in the 13th minute and never lets up again. Melodic happiness ensues (with Loose Ends teases) and continues to build into peak after glorious peak.
First version of the 2023 touring season shows the potential and the spaces it will reach in the coming weeks; more extended than late 2022 but not quite there yet.

data.footnote: With Star Wars theme tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Standard until the last few minutes where the jam breaks into a serene and beautiful soundscape. Nice sly "Star Wars" tease from Peter.

Begins in a percussive and funky zone with great Trevor but Rick takes it into some more evil zones. Everyone locks in under his heavy shredding on a series of great builds before Spuds picks up the pace and a glorious peak is achieved.
Great opener begins a fantastic segment of music in the ensuing "Hollywood Nights" and "Bob Don" before finishing "Echo."

Peter leads the way into a blissy progression in a heated initial jam section. Breaks into dark, sparse funk with nasty, nasty clav and then an ascending and powerful riff. Serious growl and mojo to this ending with Trevor going absolutely wild.

Extended Trevor solo kicks off jam & finds a beautiful theme that is quickly picked up/repeated by Rick/Peter in gorgeous interplay. After Pete solo & return to Trevor’s theme, Ben goes 2X time as band soars through multiple peaks & explosive finish.

Did this kick off the show of 2023, or does it just make you think it does? No matter, the energy, propulsiveness, and endless riffing from Rick leads to a well-earned peak, which spills over at 13:28 to a late-night percussive jam. No let-up on Night 5!
Ripping start begins to transform and almost transition into a full "Can't Get You Outta My Head" jam before returning to a beautiful high energy "Rum" finish.
Tight, focused, powerful.
Another exploration journey hitting many of the same themes we saw from the August 22 versions (funk, some darkness/tension) yet does not go as far out.

The sun beats down as the galleon plods rhythmically through the gentle open ocean. An alarm cry from the crows nest. The quiet sea begins to boil as the terrible mecha phoenix of the Enemy rises from the water and into the sky. Cries of terror and resignation as the creature bursts aflame and slams its wings into the hull in a furious rage, capsizing and igniting the vessel as the horribly blackened crew all sink lifelessly to their demise.
Show-opening version makes the 2023 "Rockdale" double-time pivot and hits a series of great peaks before returning home. The beginning of the song's jamming resurgence.

Epitome of patient style found in early 2023. Slowly yet relentlessly building, band finds themselves in dark frenzy. Just when you think it has hit its climax, they find another gear & an absolutely devastatingly thrilling peak. Winner of JOTY 2023.

data.footnote: Double time version. With W.S. Walcott Medicine Show teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Some accuse this jam of being too slow, but it's a testament to Goose 2023 that they were able to find the space in the back half of this near-30min exploration, and just linger there in conversation. Absolutely gorgeous textures from Peter.

First "Drip" to fully break into open-ended jamming. Displaying dexterity of the song, the band explores rawk-ish groove before drifting into a fully-connected hypnotic space. Bringing things home with a stunning peak, the jam resolves spectacularly.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Honeybee tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Rocking first jam and despite not fully returning to the song, kicks off a second jam that will go down in bliss history. Another example of beautiful, gorgeous, patient jamming that ends in majestic hose.

data.footnote: With Feel It Now and Bubblehouse teases.
data.jamchartnote: Ends off the "Cleveland Cali-fecta." All five members lock in on a funkier-than-normal groove and explore it for nearly 15 minutes.
For the first time in 2023, they extend the outro of "Slow Ready." Settling on a laid-back motif akin to "Eminence Front," Vintage Vibe dominates the jam for a really solid and danceable section.
A fun and bouncy arpeggiator jam in place of a Delta-esque jam makes for a unique outing and serves as a turning point in the energy of this show.
Grungier jam gains momentum steadily and leads to energetic yet powerfully soulful crescendo into hose.
What’s better than a gorgeous patient Eminence Front-like building peak? How about a brilliant cooldown only to build up to a raging, frenetic second peak!
Peter’s Nord synth dominates, ultimately finding a repeating synth loop as jam escalates around it. Excellent slightly darker build with typical raging finish.
Energetic and powerful, a simple repeating riff by Peter at 16:41 is latched on almost immediately by the rest of the band leading to a chaotic, must hear finish.

data.footnote: With Peter on bass, Rick on drums, Trevor on guitar, Spuds on percussion, and Jeff on keys.
data.jamchartnote: Fans of the Bingo Tour "Rotation Jam" should seek this out for fun instrument-swapping (and fans of this "Lee" should check out its 6/19/20 counterpart).

data.footnote: Vibey Tumble. Played with regular Tumble composed section and jam.
data.jamchartnote: Tumblé with gorgeous jamming > regular Tumble composed finish > funkfest > melodic rockfest > chaotic finish.
No jam makes a bigger case that 2023 is the Year of Big T like this one. Aggressive bass thumping leads to an epic Trevor solo and funk-strutting, blazing finish.
Dark synthy ambience > magical watery bliss > melodic soaring (very similar to 3/10/22 "Rockdale") > raging "Madhuvan" finish. Fantastic improv journey.

data.footnote: With You Haven't Done Nothin' and Loose Ends teases.
data.jamchartnote: Overly tipsy on moonshine after the Stevie Wonder show, our feathered hero stumbles into the local honky tonk joint. Unexpectedly finding himself in the midst of a racous barroom brawl, he puts his drunken Kung Fu skills to work and deftly ties up some loose ends.

The third "Double time version" sees the jam quickly slow down into murky, hypnotic, watery space courtesy of Trevor and copious amounts of delay. Multiple sessions of whale calls, and a fiery screaming guitar solo over a full band groove, round out this must hear "Borne."

data.footnote: With Teakwood Betz tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Excellent listening / subtleness w/ combination of melodic, grunginess & darkness, as Peter shifts sounds w/ various effects on guitar and keys. Trevor, Ben & Jeff also active as Rick hangs back in support until 16th minute driving a ripping peak.

data.footnote: 80s synth version. With Welcome to Delta jam and After Midnight teases from Peter and Trevor.
data.jamchartnote: Gorgeous Pete soloing out of Delta as jam stays type 1 until it slowly begins to transform into experimental chaos and darkness. Finishes with synthy funk and stop/start jamming.

data.footnote: With Ghostbusters Rap teases from Trevor.
data.jamchartnote: Absolute ripper until 18 minutes in when band settles into funky, synthy slow jam followed by a gorgeous blissy cooldown, and finally ending majestically and triumphantly by building back into a soaring melodic peak. Brilliant improv journey.

Typical "Echo" jam follows a more concise version of its counterpart from Philly, slowly and deliberately building momentum until a boiling and fiery peak is reached. Cools and -> to an incredible "Inside Out."
Taking this Spoon cover for a ride, band goes through a gradual, triumphant climb then settling down into a patient groove that transitions to "Silver Rising."
After some "25 or 6 to 4" teasing by Trevor, jam begins to gain momentum until it becomes a raging runaway steam train. One of the most outrageous build and peaks you will hear from Goose.

data.footnote: Vibey Tumble. Played with regular Tumble composed section and jam. Unfinished.
data.jamchartnote: Second vibey "Tumble" of the spring has a now well-practiced transition to the regular jam. While it's long, it doesn't do a whole lot until a break for funkier play that transitions nicely -> to "Loose Ends."
18 minutes of rock 'n roll music. Rick takes the lead and explores every inch of the jam over a steady choogle from the rest of the band. Excellent clav.

Percussive vintage vibes led first jam dissolves laterally from its peak into a Trevorbass dance clinic accented by loads of tasteful synth work. Abrupt -> Radiohead's "Weird Fishes".  Fans of 11/6/21 are advised to check this version out.

The initial blossoming of "EMG" as a second-set jam vehicle. Propelling into a vicious minor-key jam, Rick does some serious shredding but the real power lies with the rhythm section - Trevor is active and leading while Spuds keeps his foot to the floor throughout. Blasts through several screaming peaks.

data.footnote: Blind Melon. With Dark Star tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: The jam stays relatively quiet and contemplative with excellent Vintage Vibe foundation from Peter. Rick toys with melodic leads but eschews a peak as Peter throws in a "Dark Star" tease in the last moments.
Unassuming 12-minute runtime for this song - but it covers a LOT of ground in a relatively short frame.

data.footnote: Slow, melodic version. With Factory Fiction teases.
data.jamchartnote: Stunning melodic beauty followed by "Factory Fiction" inspired jam and peak.

Drummers lock in on the primal toms as Peter unleashes both synth and Vibe. Major-key vamp emerges as Rick chops up rhythm guitar. Peaks hard and gets klezmer-ish before building into "Get The Funk Out Ma Face."

data.footnote: Fast version. With Camino teases from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Longest jam to date. Multi-sectional behemoth. Cathartic bliss begins as band shakes off PA issues. "Loose Ends" hints lead into a deep funk "Camino" jam as TREVOR BASS makes the filth even filthier. From there, Rick leads into a segment similar to "SOS" or the "Crosseyed and Painless" intro jam as Peter warms up on Vibe. A final pivot into a long, evil build similar to the Philly "Echo" with some foot-guitar action from Peter explodes back into the song. Fully engaging throughout.

data.footnote: Peter Gabriel. With Streets of Cairo tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: 21-minute version accentuated by lovely Peter soloing while Rick and Ben sync up in a repeating pattern (to find almost same pattern at the close).
Brought all the way down with around 9 minutes to go only to be slowly and melodically built back up. Joyous finish.

A serious triumph for fans of patient and psychedelic Goose. Everyone hangs back and just chills in the space as Rick influences with heavy delay and echo loops. Peter soaks it all up with thick Vintage Vibe works as the rhythm section holds it all down. Increases in intensity yet remains calm through a haze of synthesizer and Goedde's light curtain. Unreal.

Getting 2nd set opener treatment, jam turns darker and more exploratory than we’ve seen from "Empress" to date after typical rocking start. After soaking in this space, Ben goes double time and Pete turns on lasers for shredding alien abduction.
Gentle, delicate start that patiently builds to wonderful soaring peak before beautifully melting away into "Peggy-O."
Clav-driven funk to start and finishing with fire, this version is a raging, emphatic ending to an unbelievable stretch of music that began with "Borne."
Come for the typical rocking start and final peak, stay for the absolute beautiful melodic bliss around 11:45-14:45.
In place of the usual jam, this unfinished Myst drops immediately into 5 minutes of gorgeous spacey "Dragonfly" vibes which become a fullblown intro -> "Dragonfly."
After a typical amount of expected choogle, this "Liz" veers stunningly into a pensive full-band bliss jam.
Patient, building funkfest. Great example of the band locking in and no one taking less, resulting in fantastic collective jamming.
Slow building groove with a ripper of a finish. The last few minutes of the jam are truly spectacular.
You can feel good about this "Madhuvan" as band finds a blissfully gorgeous peak powered by a familiar Trevor bass line.
Hints of darkness early on are quickly abandoned in favour of a now-standard double-time jam within "Rockdale." An abrupt and succinct "Loose Ends" is sandwiched within.
Fans of 11/16/19 and 11/17/22 will be familiar with this uplifting chord progression. Nothing new, but DAMN good.
Peter and Trevor lay down a sick, yet simple repeating riff, drums power the jam forward and Rick finishes in style.

Wonderful multi-section adventure. After typical rocking early jamming, band impressively breaks down jam completely patiently & comfortably living in quiet subtle improv, before gaining speed to a raging peak & returning to "Tumble" finish.

data.footnote: With Neal Francis on keys and vocals, Josh Schwartz on baritone saxophone, Greg Sanderson on tenor saxophone, and Chris Brouwers on trumpet.
data.jamchartnote: Sit-ins from Neal Francis on keys and The Horn Section make this a standout and amazing rendition. Awesome energy throughout.
Fantastic building jam resulting in absolute shredfest. Gorgeous wind down ending.

Opens the second set with 20 mins of pure fire. Peter leans into some vicious clav riffing as the energy peaks and saves Rick on a technical difficulty. Brief minute of major key jamming and they wrap it up on a strong note.

After the initial funk, the jam departs "Tumble" proper and opens up on the back of a repeated riff from Peter on upright piano. Synths come in as the rest of the band coalesces around the leadership for a while before Rick takes the reins and blasts into a strong finish. Absolutely stunning version.
ElizaCautionBeth -  first jam rockfest  with multiple builds that shifts slightly darker and slower as it begins a restrained descent into an incredible "Caution" segue.

ElizaCautionBeth -  Peter hitting creepy notes & Rick begins playing "Caution" notes out of an amazing segue. This leads to a cool, slower song start. Final verses speed up and jam builds beautifully back into "Elizabeth."
ElizaCautionBeth -  part three of this epic sandwich and as band slides beautifully back to this short but happy "Elizabeth" finish.
"Welcome to Delta"-ish jam gives way to a Rick led shredfest that eventually melts into an airy exit into "Dripfield."
Heavy vocal effects establish a psychedelic atmosphere right off the bat. The trippy vibe stays throughout the jam with haunting marimba layered over an excellent Drip drums backbone.
Excellent two-guitar shred. Peter leans into the waves of sound during the last dark build.

Another notch in the belt of the early '23 "Borne" dominance. The must-hear jam starts out minimalistic and hypnotic, similar to the Eugene version. Peter pushes the band out of the murkiness and into some dark jamming which leads to a hair-raising and triumphant peak.

A jam that Peter would write home about, two guitar Goose locks in immediately. Peter finds a nasty repeating hook at 14:20 that band centers and builds around. In 19th minute, band cools jam down and a few minutes later Peter begins soloing melodically and beautifully on the keys. Goose slowly and magically builds around Pete once again and finishes in gorgeous fashion.

The sonic equivalent of a 50 megaton hydrogen bomb, this arena rock jam oozes fun and flirts with the "Hollywood Nights" chord progression as Rick solos like an erupting volcano over some truly incendiary full band interplay.

data.footnote: With Look Out Cleveland tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Surprise 25-min excursion in a 90-min festival set. Two-guitar darkness fakes out a return to home but instead embarks into straight hose before deconstructing into solid exploration. Extremely diverse themes throughout.
Another masterclass in drums and percussion drive the majority of this jam. Last few minutes highlighted by Peter's haunting keys as guitar/synth effects and bass provide the perfect backdrop.

For the Bird’s first big amphitheater outing, “November Rain” and “Layla” codas hatch a tiny chick and implant it deep within your amygdala, pecking squarely at your heartstrings in a crescendoing symphony. Paralyzed by pangful euphoric blinding rapture, the soul inflates as a metaphysical supernova, slowly bursting through… departing… leaving vacancy in your Earthly shell for the Wolf to take hold.

This single-jam version moves into a bouncy danceable space that feels like something that might evolve from a second jam. Probably organic but possibly an intentional nod to the historical focus on electronic music at Resonance.

Peter goes crazy on this "Arrow": synthy dreaminess, marimba dance style jamming, helicopter and alarm horn background effects, subtle voice drops (woo’s?), double guitar darkness. Once he shifts back to melodic keys you know final drive to peak is coming (and it delivers!).
Typical mellow start until Ben begins tribal drumming, Rick changes to a grungier tone and jam thrusts into a nasty rock build.

Extra raunchy clav by Peter kicks off before the switch to piano gives Rick the space to start laying the foundation for what becomes a frantic journey through a sonic maze. The 13 minute mark begins the fast tempo escape from the morass. Soaring guitar work by Rick builds the jam to a couple really nice peaks before reentry.

data.footnote: With Jake Cinninger on guitar and Joel Cummins on keys.
data.jamchartnote: The Umphress Of Organos (Umphrey’s McGee sit-in): after the typical beautiful Trevor solo, Joel Cummins & Pete trade off on keys wonderfully then hand over to Jake Cinninger & Rick for a diabolical, multi-part shredfest.

Rick hits a repeating pattern that band lock on around, Pete beautifully hits a perfectly timed synth and then jam energetically takes off in best version to date. Rick is an absolute rock god in this absurdly beautiful finish.
Groove locks in and departs "Yeti" proper before one of the band's best segues to date into "Creatures."

Perfect segue out of "Yeti" and it's all gravy from there. Energy on top of energy on top of energy for 20 minutes while fireworks begin going off in the background. The following "Arcadia" finishes out a wild trio to celebrate the 4th on the boardwalk.
Not an atypical version musically or very long, but the 4th of July fireworks and INSANE energy make this one special.
Pete given a mid-jam opportunity to shine on the keys and after a quick solo, creates a salsa-like groove that band picks up on. First version to have the fast, “happy” "Dripfield" ending.

data.footnote: With Secret Agent Man tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Trevor driving as he often does with "Thatch," but this time with simple-yet-cool riffs and melodies that the band latches onto and then builds around. Stank face inducing rock in the last 6 minutes.

Foregoing the initial rocking section and peak we’ve seen in many 2023 versions, the band immediately settles for a quieter, gentler jam. Results in Rick finding a pretty riff with around 5 mins to go that everyone hooks onto and builds into a really pretty glory peak.

Goose begins taking a gentler approach than the usual Hot Tea and finds a gorgeous pocket of melodic bliss and patiently and beautifully builds around it. Heart-warming, smile-inducing joy in a way that very few bands can induce.
Very Floyd-like section gives a really psychedelic vibe to the first half of this version.

Kicking off a stretch of great jamming in their first visit to SPAC, starts with lovely Pete and Rick solos & then confidently packs an extra punch, taking the jam on one of its longest rides and leading to a gorgeous, energetic final 4 minutes (capped by Trevor Bass).

Extended, spicy Trevor and Peter solos to start the jam as crowd energy comes through the recording.  Rick comes in hot for a minute but band decides to shift and explore. Dynamic, energetic rocking continues to build in intensity until darker chaos takes over, finally releasing into joyous finish. Will take set opener Empress any day!

Jam quickly mellows out into a quiet-yet-tight groove. "Tequila" teasing adds some flavour as the band gradually increases the energy and explodes. Amazing mid-set version from the legendary SPAC debut.

Tribal, triumphant set 2 closer of an epic show. Sit back and enjoy Ben and Jeff put on a percussive masterclass while synths swirl and Rick brings down the house with a thrashing, thunderous finish. "Happy" Dripfield ending and synths continue while band walks off stage.

Fitting encore for their largest show to date, band almost stops playing after final verse and toys with spacey effects before epic build up into passionate, conquering jam full of swagger. Return to fast, melodic style as the band seems intent to burning the venue to the ground in their final moments on stage.
Fall tour opens with a blazing hot "Drive" that sees the band stretch out the solo section into some great dual-guitar madness.

"Flee" had a pretty good Fall and it all started here. Right when the rocking jam is about to wrap up with the closing guitar solo, this unfinished version instead veers into a delightfully whimsical little passage akin to early 90's Frisell interpreting ragtime music. Peter moves from vibes to clav in a satisfying fashion during a slick transition into "Look Out Cleveland".
Synthy, psychedelic vibe largely thanks to Spuds' pounding toms and Peter's delayed Vintage Vibe work. Really incredible use of keyboard effects.

This Boston run was Vintage Vibe heaven. Peter lays it on THICK, infusing vibrato and distortion into the heavy chords in the early dark segment as Rick shreds alongside. Makes a bright shift and soars through a series of glorious peaks before returning home.

Second big Boston "E or A?" of 2023. Jam begins to break into space with some octave-up from rick and reverb-drenched marimba from Peter, though still anchored in the song's progression. Second half hits double-time and explodes outward into a sunny afternoon of a peak. Just nonstop momentum.

Dark and synthy. Learning lessons from each version on the road to Boston, this one has some amazing eerie texturing from Peter, while Rick and Trevor growl in the darkness. Gradually picks up steam with the same ominous Prophet synth undertone throughout. Excellent display of tension-building here.

An important stop on the journey to the insanity at Red Rocks in just a few weeks, we are treated to another dive into Vintage Vibe darkness as the rhythm section holds down a beautiful bedrock for Rick and Peter to weave around each other. Run through a brick wall with the momentum of this one.

data.footnote: With Taylor Goldsmith on guitar and vocals, Griffin Goldsmith on drums, and Jeff on guitar.
data.jamchartnote: Featuring Taylor and Griffin of Dawes. Huge version has some great guitar interplay in the first half before setting into glorious bliss land for the second half. Jeff loves that D chord!

Initial two-guitar duelling fragments into marimba space and slows down into some classic Fall '23 bliss-building. Hints of the reverse "Heartbreaker" riff Rick loves so much punch through at the peak before Peter leads into a piano-centric outro jam that might just be the best part of the whole thing.

Elizabliss chugs right into a gorgeous, intoxicating bliss jam that smoothly builds and builds to a triumphant peak, with Rick’s guitar tone sparkling like the Champagne of beers in the Miller High Life Theatre.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Somebody's Watching Me teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Straight into disco mode. Peter sets up the synths and works the delay on his clav as the groove expands. He then moves over to Vibe as the dance gets slightly darker before a PERFECT -> to "Echo."

-> in from "Myst." Picks up where the groove left off and builds up a powerful head of steam before heading smoothly into "Take On Me," finishing out an excellent trio of songs to begin the second set.

data.footnote: 80s synth version. With Welcome to Delta jam.
data.jamchartnote: Never really departs the Delta space but has some excellent Peter exploration of tones on clav and Vintage Vibe. A fun listen.
Spacey and textural with hints of "Dragonfly." Gets funkier out of the murk with a laid-back vibe and hits a series of bluesy rock peaks almost like the 10/4/22 "This Old Sea."

Spuds quickly turns percussive as Peter hits repeating patterns on the Vibe. Fragments into the Eastern-tinged space they love so much with circular riffs from Rick and Peter that give it a very dissonant and darker feel.

A rare fully-two-guitar jam for 2023. Deconstructs into a seriously groovy interplay section driven by Spuds' clap stack. Still pretty much Type I throughout but a very fun and groovy listen. Peter hits the keys right at the end with hints of Ted Tapes riffing as they > to an explosive "Red Bird."

Whether you think it's the JOTY or not, this "Thatch" is a seriously dense listen. Dark and percussive at first, it feels very typical for the tour but quickly heads into evil territory thanks to Rick and Peter's interplay.
