Spuds pivots into a charging beat at the 18th minute and they just go for it. Superlatives can't even do this peak justice - needs to be listened. Rick plays with his Whammy at the apex before they execute a perfect and towering return to the song proper. All-timer.
Very "In Your Eyes"-tinged jam. Upbeat and feel-good, this version signifies that Goose is finally finding their footing with big "Dripfield" jams and breaking the mold.

Standard fare until the last five minutes or so, when the band breaks into some terrifyingly evil improv. Layers of dark textures thanks to Peter's synths and clav while Rick opts for some more laid-back riffing. One of the best segments of the tour.
The third festival "Kylie" of the year breaks from form in an amazing "Elmeg the Wise"-like jam. Triumph.
data.songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head

data.jamchartnote: Eschews the usual blistering and fast-paced jam in favour of a laid-back and major-key space. Shorter version that will draw you in for repeated listens.

Peppy jam begins with Spuds on punchy tom work as Peter lays into the Vibe. Turns spacey and then falls away into a bouncy funk jam that feels totally unique to Goose's sound. Trevor and Rick lock in on some riffs while Peter moves to a textural role throughout the contemplative and unhurried groove. Must-listen to understand the developmental period of Fall '23.

Another stellar outing for the song in '23, this Liz finds herself ever-so-gently tugging at threads of the bay area "Dark Star" concentrate in the fabric, pulling Inspiration from the cosmos for the truly gorgeous bliss jam to come.

Not your average set-closing rocker. The band moves beyond standard Peter shred territory to an all-out party jam with a euphoric feel. Foot on the gas, it peaks for several minutes straight before sliding back into the song proper.

Second big "Drip" of fall tour breaks form into the familiar percussive play with Rick and Peter dancing around each other. Sticks in this zone for a while until a shift into an amazing and expressive bliss-rock peak. Beautiful stuff.

While many previous versions of "Thatch" highlight an aggressive or darker jam, this LA version turns bright and contemplative after a turn of percussive play with strong Trevor and Peter underneath Rick's melodies. Hints of the Vegas "Elizabeth" to come a few days later.

This fluid and vibrant Flee is at its best during the masterful emotive solo Rick guides the first half of the jam with, Peter dancing along with every note in some of his very finest piano accompaniment.

Choogles along as normal until the 11th minute, when Peter and Trevor lock in on a major-key transition. Rick flips on the octave-up overtop a low synth drone as Goose takes it really slow and patient in a build that reminds some of "Pancakes" or "Wolfman's Brother." Whatever you want to call it, it's absolutely phenomenal. Special highlight to the gong TEXTURES that Jeff lays down.

data.footnote: With Magic School Bus theme tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Peter hits the Vibe early on in the jam as the pace is set. Fun "Magic School Bus" teases pivot into a great peak section that make this the standout OG "AIN" since 2019.
Haunting reverse-delay Vibe early section goes full shred-hose for a wild peak.

First jammed version of "Sea" in 2023 gets bluesy and rocking. Rick toys with a riff similar to Zeppelin's "Moby Dick" as Peter whales on the organ. Guitar takes over as the band hits a feel-good peak and just sustains it for a long time.

Newly rearranged "EMG" jam segment is perfectly suited to the pure evil that develops at Red Rocks. Locking in on a theme like the hallowed 1/30/22 "Wysteria" and 6/10/22 "AIN," Rick just doesn't let up for a second as Spuds and Jebb go wild on the primal drums. Trevor drops massive bombs as Peter hammers piano chords and the darkness just BUILDS. Absolutely astounding improv.
Closes the first set like its recent counterpart in Oakland. Gets outside of standard "Yeti" for some fun peak jamming.
Continuation of the mellower and more upbeat "Thatch" style seen at the Wiltern on 9/28. Rocking first half transitions into a quieter space that builds into an excellent peak.

This top shelf "Factory Fiction" jam begins with a snarling slow burn. Eventually finding its way into a patiently developed anthemic Rick-led "Dragonfly" jam, this sonic assault on the alien landscape of Red Rocks concludes in an explosive fashion that merits repeat listens.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Magic School Bus tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Tech issues with Rick's mic cause the band to bail on the song after the first verse and just jam. A strong Type I peak is reached before Peter hits the Vibe and infuses "Magic School Bus" into the groove. Smoothly goes from there into a more evil space thanks to Rick's shredding and peaks nicely.
data.venuename: West Lawn at Lory Student Center

data.jamchartnote: Moving with peak efficiency this "Red Bird" drops into darkness more quickly than a Spirit Halloween can fill the void of a dead retail store. The summoned Avian Entity arrives and decides to have a bit of fun on this day. Playfully tugged at like psychic marionettes, the members of Goose channel an impromptu film score to the River Spirit’s arrival at the Aburaya Bathhouse, tapping “Moby” to complete the scene.
data.venuename: West Lawn at Lory Student Center

data.jamchartnote: Second song ever played in Europe goes full bliss rock mode. Soaring first jam, crunchy middle segment, and then another excellent peak to close.

Peter runs marimba through the Leslie for a haunting and unique effect early on. Rick and Trevor lock in on some melodies as the effects continue to dominate. The band emerges as Spuds picks up the pace and seems to be heading for bliss land, but Peter delays that shift with layers and layers of reverbed piano. Eventually hits a blistering peak and returns home.
Trevor and Peter find a really catchy repeating downward progression theme that the band builds around. Excellent gradual collective cool down that allows band to side into "Borne."

Surprise jam out of this cover gets dark and nasty with layered Leslie marimba and organ from Peter while Spuds absolutely punishes his kit. Can't tell if it's the band or crowd screaming here either!

Highlight of the Jamsterdam show, Peter shines as he drives mood of jam with simple yet powerful selections on keys throughout, ending in beautiful Blissteria collective band magic. Slides into a really great "Electric Avenue."
Eugene "Borne"-style jamming for the middle few minutes as the band gets atypically quiet and patient. Layers of textures are absolutely breathtaking and it's a shame it's so short!
Peter collects a bunch of coins early on as the rhythm section destroys the minimalist funk groove. Rick pivots into triumph and the band unleashes a volcanic peak to close it out.

data.footnote: 80s synth version. With Welcome to Delta jam and After Midnight tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Gorgeous bliss finish.

data.footnote: With Welcome to Delta tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Type I high energy scorcher.
Short, fiery jam not to be missed. Band finds the same downward progression from the Cologne "Echo" and absolutely shreds the peak.
In typical Euro Tour 23 fashion, short, type 1, yet impressive jam. Melodic and uplifting finish before landing into "Fifth of Beethoven."
Strap in - short but shredfest peak showing you can't skip even 8 minute jams with Goose.

First Type II "Animal" ever departs from form after 13 mins into a contemplative major-key space. A gorgeous and soaring peak ensues with great contributions from all five before Spuds leads into a "Flodown"-esque section before the song closes unfinished.

With an extra twinkly intro courtesy of Peter, this "Inside Out" moves into some blues-tinged guitar jamming that briefly borders on your typical "Animal" jam territory (band must have been feeling inspired from earlier) before a Trevorbass & keys section closes it out.

Longest "Lee" to date doesn't go too far from home, at least initially, as Peter dials up some synth undertones. Hits on some "Dragonfly" elements before Spuds takes control as he was wont to do on the Europe '23 tour. Peter plays with motif's almost like Vulfpeck's "Tee Time" as Rick shreds up to the finish.

Free-flowing, collective no-one-take-the-lead improv as you can find little moments throughout where any 2 band members riff of each other only to have the others join in. Gradual, patient build leading to explosive peak.

Quickly heads for Winter 2022-style dark jamming. Trevor gets DEEP into Spuds' pocket as Rick's angular soloing swirls around Peter's eerie piano. Synths come in as it gets heavier and into some carnival-like zones before the band bails back into the "Echo" ending.
Immediately dropping into a darker key akin to the Red Rocks version, this jam pulsates and is driven forward by ferocious drumming, slowly building to majestic glorious rock.
After funky start where Luigi finds his coins, Peter layers mystical synths and Rick finds a haunting repeating riff that propels a wonderfully unique and enchanting version. Thrilling finish.

Blistering Type I play cools into a brief "Shama" fakeout before Goose unleashes one of the best bliss jams in recent memory. Calling to mind the Cap "Drive," each member takes their time with the theme and delivers an absolutely incredible peak.

After Peter tells crowd they have one more song, Rick rips back into a second Drive jam to end the show. A fiery theme develops and eventually morphs into the "(dawn)" finish. Incredible spontaneous moment.

Peter stays on guitar for the entire jam, an exceptionally rare occurrence for the time period. Some nasty Type I churn explodes through the first part of the jam but cools around 13:30. Peter's staccato repeated riff informs the next part of the jam, where the band plays with a theme akin to the ending of "Dripfield." Great upbeat groove modes.

Summoning the ghost of the ‘21 Legend Valley "Madhuvan," this sub-14-minute version contains an incredible stop/start jam, alternating back and forth between peaceful serenity and possessed heavy metal shredding.
Dance fest that brings an extra bit of juice to the party. Ripping extended finish.

Builds momentum like many '23 versions but begins to stray from normal when Peter hits the clav with some subtle delay. Spuds is an absolute WORKHORSE as he keeps the propulsive tempo up. Rick finds a melody that he likes and Goose shreds to a peak of epic proportions. Final night of tour throw-down.

“DDS”/“The Doctor Will See You Now” vocal shenanigans lead to gorgeous bliss. Ben eventually hits double time and jam builds to soaring, beautiful first climax. In 16th minute, they return to traditional "Madhuvan" rocking. Peter takes lead with a few playful piano solos before Rick storms back in for an another blistering peak. Just when you think it may be winding down in minute 21, band rips back in and explodes the finish. One of the best jams, if not the best, of Euro Tour 23.

data.footnote: Began as slow, melodic version and switched to “fast” version after the first chorus.
data.jamchartnote: For the first time ever, Goose combines the original and "slow" arrangements of "AIN" as part of the Echochrome planet theme. Jam is solid but the real star is Peter's RIPPING ending guitar solo.

The 20-minute Justin Timberlake cover you ordered! Begins with hints of "Eugene Borne" as synths swirl before taking off into a more familiar peak zone that touches themes akin to Ted Tapes cut "Camino II." Superb all around.

data.footnote: With Ghostbusters Rap tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Standard play for the majority of the jam breaks into an excellent full-band rhythmic motif for the last five minutes. All about the drums here.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Animal tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Rare mid-first-set "Drip" returns to arena status with a high-octane Type II peak. Great stuff, fades unfinished.

Not your average "strap in" CCR cover. Peter hits the Vibe as the jam begins and the band embarks on a wildly spacey Type II journey that eventually winds around to the conclusion of "Echo of a Rose." Look for this song again in 2024.

data.footnote: With Jungle Boogie tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: A fitting conclusion to the tenth Goosemas that also was Spuds' final song - though we didn't know at the time. Nothing out of the ordinary but a special, fiery "Arcadia" that takes some extra spins around the ending as the band took a moment to relish their Hampton accomplishment.

Cotter's first big jam and the band does not hold back one iota. First developing a ripping dual-guitar jam for several minutes - very active Trevor - before Cotter seamlessly transitions into the "second jam." Patiently builds into a bliss motif reminiscent of the ending of "SOS," peaking massively and concluding just short of the 31-minute mark.

Not multi-section like the first set's "Drive" but is at least as good. Chaos slowly begins to creep in as Rick introduces a dark melody to build upon as Cotter really shows what he can do. Perfect re-entry atop the peak as Rick gradually teases the ending "Pancakes" riff a number of times before committing to the landing. Must-hear.

Revised arrangement with propulsive drumming from Cotter leads to a jam that could not be more different from Fall '23 versions. Initially winds up in a great blissy space that reaches a natural conclusion, but the band instead opts to put the pedal to the metal and strike into a dance groove. Peter hits into some filthy envelope filter clav work before transitioning into marimba while Rick slowly guides the band back into the euphoric conclusion of the song.
First version with Jeff on acoustic guitar and it sounds great. Jam coalesces into a cool groove before sliding perfectly -> to "Factory Fiction," probably the most notable thing about this one.

After an energetic and extended jam, Goose begins to slowly morph into one of the most feel good, happy, grin-inducing jams they've ever played. A jam so happy, it’s like watching the entirety of Ted Lasso season one in 30 seconds.

A breathtaking and beautiful take on the song. Doesn't stray far from "Rosewood" proper but showcases remarkable patience as the band builds together to a dreamlike peak. Rick throws in some excellent dark tension-building moments toward the end as well.

Great dual-guitar churn on the front end, but the last few minutes of deconstructive and contemplative play are the real star. Showed potential for further exploration but was abandoned in favour of a concise "Echo of a Rose."
Dark and propulsive jam led by Peter on the OB-6. Not the deepest improvisationally but an excellent listen.

The band spends the first minutes after the vocal rounds poking at the edges of the melody until finally casting the bit. Then it's drill, baby, drill. The jam loops, but with purpose. It takes a pointed journey, uncovering new layers as it spirals deeper into the core of its oblique melody, creating an ever-changing tapestry of sound. Cotter energetically closes his first "Bird" with rolling tom work over creative breakbeats while Rich toys with an almost Middle Eastern "Minarets"-style riff.

Jam begins from nothing as Rick begins to build a sinister motif. Peter lays down delayed Vibe as the rest of the band enters and gradually build into a beautifully evil churn. Rick then signals to Cotter at the apex and the drums drive forward into double-time, bringing us home in a blaze of glory to bookend this second set. Some really wild and articulate heavy metal builds from Rick.
First jammed version since 10/6/22 gets into an airy space quickly with Rick sticking to form at first.

Peter goes full Cory Wong mode on the initial jam segment as he takes a stroll around the stage. Eschewing the typical B-flat modulation to go into jam territory, the band fragments out of the funk and quickly builds into gorgeous major-key play led by Vintage Vibe and Rick's emotional soloing. Cotter picks up the tempo post-peak and Rick lets Peter take the lead as they blaze into the finish of an excellent jam and set.

data.footnote: Vampire Weekend. FTP. With Ezra Koenig on guitar and vocals, Chris Tomson on drums, Chris Baio on bass, and Jessica tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: The fabled 31-minute "Cape Cod" of Vampire Weekend dreams. Cotter and CT really lock in here as the band gets into uncharted territory. Hits some Allman Brothers bliss (much to the excitement of Rick and Ezra), then some great clav funk ahead of the song's conclusion. "Those guys can hang!"
A good omen for 2024, "Arrow" makes good use of its time in the first outing of the year. The band drops into a late-night OB-6 space for a while before an explosive conclusion.

data.footnote: With Welcome to Delta and Dripfield teases from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Goes absolutely balls-to-the-walls for the first jam, getting to high speeds and intensity while Rick absolutely unleashes on the eager crowd. Back half is a nice and patient dual-guitar space that segues nicely into "Dripfield" to complete the Driptych.

Rick's rig suffers from some technical difficulties, so the rest of the band takes the time by hanging out in some gorgeous ambience with a commitment to patience and quieter dynamics. Especially incredible melodic work from Trevor. Rick rejoins toward the end and nudges the band into "Silver Rising."
data.venuename: Clune Auditorium at Wilton High School

data.jamchartnote: It's your classic festival set "Myst" -> "Kylie"...until it's not. Amazing textures in a synth-drenched wind-down on the outro.
data.songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head

data.jamchartnote: A sludgy and mysterious exit from the song structure leads to some typical jamming that progressively gets more melodic over the course of 12 minutes or so until Rick latches onto the theme that becomes the centerpiece. He deftly builds up to the peak backed by Cotter’s staccato attack for 5 minutes of triumphant glory. We don’t know what we’ve won, but we’re certain we’re victorious.

Cotter's first "AIN" opens summer tour on a strong note. Gets into some percussive space before a brief major section gives way to a spacier and dark-tinged mode. Peter goes to guitar for the last few minutes as they explore some new territory before sliding perfectly -> to "Flee."

Initial standard "Borne" jamming gets into some weird territory just before the 20-minute mark thanks to Cotter and Trevor. Envelope filter bass gets augmented by choppy clav from Peter as Rick lays down loops, eventually smoothly morphing into an upbeat and rocking peak. Hell of an omen for the rest of tour.

Rick's new synth pedal gets a workout as the band plays the first of many amazing versions of "Empress" in summer '24. Late-night disco groove emerges, which will be a prevalent theme throughout the tour.

The band departs from initial funk together in a rocking progression with Peter laying down chunky guitar behind Rick's soloing. Downshifts with a major modulation and follows a familiar uplifting pattern as Cotter pushes the tempo. Hits a strong peak before returning to funk and hints at "Arrow" ahead of the song's conclusion.

Circular patterns of tension and darkness develop as Cotter's fluidity shines. Builds layers and layers of unease as Peter hits sirens and Rick gets dissonant. Amazing stuff that can be likened to a mid-90s "Stash."

Roaring down the open road, radio blaring “...and the road goes on forever I’ve got one more silver...”, feeling mellow mischievous, the sea pans into view. Now barreling along the cliffs the Rider abruptly plunges into the sea, radio cut dead in the depths replaced by embryonic deep whooshing saline heartbeat. Feeling a needful pull toward the surface a triumphant new driving rhythm crackles the airwaves while screaming ablaze toward shouts emanating from vermin in their wooden coffin soon-to-be a pyre.

data.footnote: The Beatles. With Welcome to Delta teases from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Blasts out of an excellent "Red Bird" into a blistering hot jam.

All-out disco dance party. First "Lee" to ever hit 20 minutes stays in a steady pocket with digital sauce from Rick and OB-6 work from Peter. Trevor steps in with a new progression that deepens the vibe as Cotter stays heavy on toms. Eventually increases in intensity and rages into the finish. Stellar version.
A gorgeous two-guitar bliss jam that unfurls into the mountain air. A mood of exuberance throughout.

The band sits in Type I "Hungersite" territory for most of the jam, giving the impression of a conscious effort to resist full peak mode for as long as possible. By the time they get there, there's some undertones of heavy rock and Cotter leads into a half-time shred mode for the final minute that's absolutely amazing.
Quickly departs "Drip" proper for a similar jam to the earlier "Wysteria." Not super long but is guaranteed to lift your spirits.

Second "Drive" of the year and second to pass 30 minutes. Hangs out in fast-paced two-guitar funk zones until the 15th minute, when Rick leads into a more atmospheric zone atop a bed of Peter's synth. Trevor gets LOW as the band finds an ascending riff akin to "Time to Flee" and works it for a while. Eventually finds its way into a piano-forward zone that seems to hint at "Factory Fiction" for a while. Lands smoothly in a set-closing "Give it Time."

Several mins of dissonance kicks off before Rick pulls the band into a funkier mode. Modulates to major and soars for a few mins - but the real work is just beginning. Digging into some evil tones with Peter laying on Vintage Vibe and then OB-6, the band builds into a massive black hole. Cotter pivots into a faster beat insinctively and Rick and Peter circle each other. Trevor blasts his way in just before the 26:00 with MASSIVE bombs before a "River Lullaby" jam develops and closes out this all-timer jam.

Hating on this "Rum" is hating on some of Rick's best guitar work of the tour. It's like a spoiled child claiming that the family trip to Disney was a disaster because they had to have cake for dessert instead of ice cream.
Pure hose. There's not necessarily a need for exploration here as the band's excitement pours out into the celebratory music.

The beginning of this is all about the Vibe textures. Peter sticks to chordal work through a big peak before the band transitions into a more propulsive zone, beginning to build momentum thanks to Peter's repeated piano and Cotter's insistence. Rick hangs back to let the drummer lead as Peter throws ideas into the space. Continuously builds in energy and intensity before a hot peak, finally closing out with a few minutes of percussive funk and interplay before abruptly swerving into "A Fifth of Beethoven."

data.footnote: With Mad World teases from Rick and Cantaloupe Island teases from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Peter keeps the familiar "Hungersite" peak fresh with a repeated descending lick, beefing up his usual comping behind Rick's solo. Barely slows down at all before the disco-delay clav comes in like this version's counterparts from 11/20/23 and Chateau Sessions. Rick throws in some digital sauce as the disco gets more vicious and hits a final peak.
First set closing jam that fools you with an initial pleasing bliss section before turning on the burners and torching Indianapolis to the ground. NSFW explosive peaking.
data.venuename: Everwise Amphitheater at White River State Park

data.jamchartnote: Steady marimba-filled groove gives most of jam a summery vibe, that begins to turn on the gas around 5.5 minutes left. Rick begins trilling and chording up higher and more melodically as the rest of band increases in volume and intensity. Gorgeous "Rosewood" heart-bursting beauty at 16:47 that resolves wonderfully.
data.venuename: Everwise Amphitheater at White River State Park

data.jamchartnote: Listening to this jam feels incomplete without taking into account the incredible sunset that happened during it. The band breaks from "E or A?" form into a long synth-drenched peak with blissful energy.

2nd huge "Lee" of the summer begins with reverbed-out clav from Peter. Coasts on synth-drenched piano and Rick's guitar which begins to lead into a darker mood. Cotter rolls on the snare as Trevor burbles up with envelope filtered work. Explores a hypnotic riff for several mins, bringing the jam to a boil before Cotter increases the tempo into a minimalist and percussive zone with Peter on marimba piano. Begins its patient journey home before returning to the conclusion of "Lee." 21 minutes of pure improv.

Blazing second set version sees the band lock in around Trevor's thumping and Peter's arpeggiator. Hypnotic groove develops and hits a peak but is brought to its conclusion by Rick before it can go any further.

With its patient commitment to quieter dynamics, the first half drips with Manzarek-style vintage vibe flurries in conversation with subtle guitar lines. As the tempo increases, both keys and guitar introduce distortion, leading the full band into the same punctuated recurring motif as the fiery Ryman "Wysteria."

Winner of the 2024 "How Much Can You Do With a Single Riff?" contest, this "Tumble" locks onto a bright bubblegum pop theme, energetically looped while stretching its sugary edges and layering subtle synth swells over syncopated marimba textures. A brief but intense Dream Theater-like detour adds a dramatic twist before gleefully returning to the composed outro.
data.venuename: Constellation Brands-Marvin Sands Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Quickly pivots from easy breezy mode into punchy clav funk. Grows thicker and heavier for several minutes until the band comes up for air and soars into a peaky zone atop Peter's synth drone. Rick's soloing has some serious mojo behind this as Goose blasts through the amazing end of this jam.

This lengthy "Arrow" takes its time to leave the bow, but, once it does, soars high and true. The band pulls every trick from the quiver, starting with juicy vintage vibes, moving into interpolated Eurythmics-style synth work, and culminating in a punchy motif in which Rick masterfully synthesizes angular phrasing and blissy peaks.

data.footnote: With Tarantella Napoletana tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Longest "Atlas Dogs" to date starts with vibrato-heavy Vibe and assertive Trevor as Rick sticks to rhythm. Octave-up chirp soloing and tom-heavy driving from Cotter hits the "Tarantella Napoletana" and peaks. Could have ended there but Cotter hits into a dance beat and Peter dials in the phased-out piano for several minutes of jamming that could have come directly from a Parcels show. Impossible not to dance.

Percussive clav funk grooves in out of the gate but the real star of this is the "When The Saints Go Marching In"-adjacent bliss jam. Patient, gorgeous, and full - it's everything you want from melodic and happy Goose.
Huge second set cover follows a similar path to the 4/7/24 "Drive" - heavy and driving dual-guitar work in the first part and an uplifting slide of piano rock to end it off. Incredible jam.
Don't ever skip a shorter "Liz" in this era. Pure energy and rock.

Two-guitar funk dissolves into a patient major key with great cymbal contributions from Jeff. Never really takes off into high-energy peak land which is a rare occurrence and segues nicely into a powerful "Bob Don."

data.footnote: With Arcadia tease from Peter and Use Me teases from Trevor.
data.jamchartnote: You enjoy this jam, beginning with some squishy OB-6 work from Peter and eventually shifting into a flowing rock zone that might inspire you to jump on trampolines.

Goose slows things down lulling the crowd into a false sense of comfort and safety. Peter begins shooting soothing space lasers and soon the Fox Theatre is being lifted into the dark skies, as the music slowly morphing into an extra-terrestrial summoning. Thick and evil music pours forth from the stage to swallow the crowd during this absolute all-time jam.

data.footnote: With Welcome to Delta tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: The summer of "Tumble" continues with this ATL heater, once again delving into serious bliss-rock territory. Kicks off a three-song set of sustained energy from band and crowd alike in fine form.
On a sweltering evening in NC, Goose opts for quiet introspection in "Borne," following Peter's thick Vintage Vibe work into a familiar major-key progression. Sunset jams.

data.footnote: Fast version. With Pancakes tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: An initial peak leads into some deeper minor-key marimba/Rick chord jamming. Peter infuses a synth drone and Rick goes for an octave-down soar, sticking to a somewhat blissy mode. Modulates for a slower psychedelic rock zone with incredible drum work atop a repeating progression before mellowing and returning home.
Grounded minor-key play is a nice departure from the synth-heavy jams of June '24. Flips to major for a spell before a grimy build brings us home.
Thick and dirty dual-guitar work for its duration. Slides cleanly into "Hollywood Nights."

A propulsive Trevor-led groove gives way to some gentle arpeggiator accentuation from Peter under a mellow Summery vibe. To round things out, a pretty descending chord progression from Rick is danced around by the band until, continuing to trend of unfinished "Mysts", there's is a fade-out > "Spirit of the Dark Horse".

The OB-6 makes the jam feel like it's in a spaceship taking off as the band leans hard into ambient space with a commitment to patience and quieter dynamics. Rick infuses digital sauce under the subtle textures as the jam gets more percussive before Peter transforms the synth into its own pulsating organism. Trevor leads into a new progression as the waves of digital sound continue. Transforms to a beauteous bliss jam not unlike the Raleigh "Pancakes" around the 18th minute and closes with an amazing peak.
Squeezing in the encore before curfew, Goose defies expectations of a standard version and delivers a brutally evil jam section within "Empress."

First mins of the jam is a funk thrown led by Big T, followed by a 10 min blissful section that continues to build into a peak around 20 min mark that can only be described as “what it’s like to see god”. In the return to Tumble peak, Rick whips out the machine gun and mows down the approaching enemy troops. The whole band, but especially Rick - epic performance, as good as music gets.
data.venuename: Mann Center for the Performing Arts

data.jamchartnote: This first jam is the Cotter show. The man is on FIRE through the usual peak and then goes hand-in-hand with Rick into an angular, dark zone for the final few minutes. A motif that is begging to be explored more by Goose.
data.venuename: Mann Center for the Performing Arts

data.jamchartnote: Wastes no time before going full clav funk. DRENCHED in reverb, Peter really digs in before transitioning to OB-6 and lifting the jam into the air. Patient bliss develops with gorgeous Rick and the soaring guitar is back in "In Your Eyes" territory before you even realize it. Longest version to date and absolutely phenomenal.
data.venuename: Mann Center for the Performing Arts

data.jamchartnote: First version ever to open a two-set performance gets into some nice rocking Type 1.5 space to kick off the band's largest show to date. Lots of fun in this slot.
The 2024 resurgence of "Yeti" continues with this digital sauce-infused party version.

Big second-set version comes on the heels of a special Autumn Crossing performance. The band strips down to minimalist funk initially with Peter really going ham with delay on the clav. All five members unite as one and rip through a sustained peak section with no one person in the lead.

A wicked parade that meanders through a demented circus and the island of misfit toys before things start to get truly weird. Angular, dissonant, and downright terrifying at times. The segment at the 20 minute mark has the whole band in perfect sync on this bad trip.   This is dark Goose at its finest. A milestone jam.
Emerging from "Skux Life," the quintet explores some nice reggae-tinged terrain before building a peak back into the ending of "Pancakes." A worthy stack, indeed.
Debut gets taken for a nice ride through airy major-key and then propulsive clav funk. Transitions very cleanly into "Drive."
Nice little Trevor Bass solo gets added to this version.
36-minute debut is quantity over quality, but the band's commitment to exploration atop Cotter's flowing groove is great.

Peter dominates this version with pulsating waves of OB-6, then matches Rick's heavy shredding on Vintage Vibe. The antithesis to September 2024's significant major-key jams and one of the month's best outings.
Some cool full-band grooving in the middle that foreshadows the improvisational development to come later in the tour.
Beautiful Moog Muse textures dominate the first jammed version since 8/17/22.
Listen for that earworm riff Peter picks up on Vibe. Excellent sustained peak.
Reminiscent of the Mann "Tumble" in its pulsating major-key groove with Peter on marimba piano - though the emotion isn't nearly as impactful.

Peter hangs back for most of the jam on subtle OB-6 work, which gives Rick and Cotter the room they need to DOMINATE. A propulsive and dark theme emerges with Rick on nonstop momentum, using Cotter's full-steam-ahead groove to destroy everything in his path. Blasts back into a high-energy finish.

Eschews the typical Type I "Hungersite" peak and shifts immediately into gorgeous bliss. Rick weaves some incredible earworm melodies to a peak before the band quiets, beginning a LONG and patient build to a final explosion. Excellent use of phaser piano from Peter.

After some quick dual-guitar riffing, Peter pivots to OB-6 and transforms the jam within a few seconds. The band goes full Ted Tapes for a while, luxuriating in an almost "Dragonfly"-like space, before Rick steers into a build based around a repeating melody. Taking on qualities similar to the final section of the 4/14/23 "Hungersite," Goose delivers one of the most breathtakingly beautiful peaks of their career to date.

The first “Sea” with the hypnotic rearranged vocal outro. Rick leads out of that bridge as the band carries the melody beneath, casually jamming toward a beautiful peak that summons more oohs and ahhs before breaking into a classic “Sea” jam. Pete layers synth over effected vintage vibes, enabling the best of what “Seas” can do: It explores space while embracing quieter dynamics, steadily escalating into a full-band-jammed power ballad. This one still had room to run when it dropped into “Interlude II.”

data.footnote: Fast version. With Please Forgive Me teases.
data.jamchartnote: No forgiveness needed in this standout version. September 2024 was a great month for short-yet-deep "Echo" jams.
The rhythm section is king in this jam, going from spacey psychedelia to driving funk. Cotter and Trevor push forward and Jeff jumps in on tambourine at the perfect time. Great full-band grooving.

Dealer’s choice between “Madhulama Ding Dong,” “Shama Lama Madhuvan,” and “Shama Lama Madhudong.” Whatever you call this gorgeous version, let its blissy jam with the “Shama” call-backs wash over you as it did the Chicago crowd on a gorgeous summer evening.

Jazz juggernaut Julian Lage sits in and grabs immediate attention with a gorgeously improvised intro guitar solo in the second consecutive jammed out version of AWS after a 2 year absence. The lead guitarists eschew the typical sit-in dogfight by bolstering each other’s playing with creative musical underscores, offering ample room to the other to work their magic.
Shades of 6/19/21 "Madhuvan" and 11/18/23 "All I Need" as the band cools things off and flips on a tension/release alternating jam.
Standard fare until the final few minutes when the band collapses into a dark and ambient loop-filled zone.

This Drip escapes the typical type 1 riffing right off the bat and leads into a thunderous take on the familiar That’s All jamming theme. The jam drifts even further from home into an ethereal dreamscape that has a tide-like quality. The undulating ebb and flow is evoked by the sophisticated full-band exploration of dynamics ranging from soft to sonorous.
The "Zaltcadia."

Infusing the 'dale with "Dragonfly" vibes? Sign us up for more of this please! This powerful "Rockdale" is the clear highlight of this set and gave fans in the Twin Cities a taste of what to expect in the upcoming second frame.
Peter and Trevor lead the way initially with the former on Vintage Vibe. Moves from a slower and spacier mode to balls-to-the-walls peaking that will have you running through several brick walls.
A particularly ferocious churn gives way to a whimsical lilting progression akin to the bonus jam in the fan-favorite 3/26/23 version.

Serious early funk puts the power of reverb/envelope filter clav on display. Picks up energy and speed before blazing through an excellent peak atop a roaring wave of synth. Second half of an excellent first-set 1-2 punch with the preceding "All I Need."

The Taco Town of “Empresses.” We start with the top slice: an unprecedented six-minute pre-verse intro jam. Then, savor the thick, crunchy layer after Trevor’s bass solo. You think you’ve reached the meat, but then you’re swept into a “River” of “Greens.” Think we’re done? Not quite. The real core of this sandwich is the bottom half, with “Empress” returning for a jam-packed, savory finish that ties it all together.

The bottom half of the "Empress" sandwich starts with the same layer that topped the "Green River" center. The band settles into a steady, chill groove, with Rick’s digital sauce poured over Pete’s thick layer of vintage vibes. This section is light but thick, a monolith revealing a slightly spicy aftertaste before dissolving into brief almost "Flowdown"-like dissonance. A final dark spread evocative of Mario’s underworld theme, coats the bottom slice’s closing verses and composed finish.
Rick hangs back with some atypical bluesy riffing. Not crazy long but unique.

data.footnote: With Crazy Train tease from Rick and Peter and Secret Agent Man tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: In its first truly extended outing for this song, a propulsive ominous groove is eventually harnessed by a sustained Seger-esque BDE rock explosion. Goose fans have been put on notice that regardless of constant name changes, whatever we're calling this song it can and will jam!
-> out of "Kylie" to complete a power hour of excellent flow. Builds in a linear fashion with the band all working in perfect lockstep. Listen for Trevor at the peak!!
Excellent chunky clav jam on the first outside-the-box version of this song.

Beautifully grimy two-guitar jam covers an insane amount of ground in its 14 minutes. Gets churning and evil and seems to be far from over when a major-key modulation winds up in an abrupt segue into the Goose debut of "True Love Waits."
Do YOU like thick funk jams? Look no further.

data.footnote: 80s synth version. With Welcome to Delta jam.
data.jamchartnote: Standard Delta jam until the last few minutes, where things get evil and Rick and Peter chase each other up and down wild and dissonant riffs. Amazing but gone too soon as Rick initiates a segue into "Big Modern!"
Peter gets some really cool synth waves out of the Nord Stage toward the end here, but Rick brings things back home before they can get too crazy.
Modulates quickly into an efficient and beautiful hose jam.

Seventeen months younger and still cutting his teeth, Eugene's baby brother enchants the neighboring northwest with a worthy, if less mature, reprise. Built on a bed of vintage vibes and a steady, pulsing bassline, the performance explores a richly textured, atmospheric space as Rick patiently vamps until finding a hook around the 14-minute mark. For the last few minutes, the band shifts to a dancier chordal groove that never fully realizes its potential, dissolving instead into "Turned Clouds."

Another great S1 closer that starts forebodingly with some minor key piano and is driven forward by tribalistic drumming. After a little tension, Rick settles back gently and melodically before band patiently and collectively builds up to EMG’s typical ripping conclusion. Cotter truly shines throughout

Grungy double guitar rock and roll takes a magical tour through blisstown. Gorgeous melodic finish before slipping into "Electric Avenue." Very reminiscent of the SPAC version from earlier in the month.

Machine gun fire drowns out the engines roar as the vehicle veers off the road in a raging inferno. Speed up. Target marked. Repeat. Targets in the rear view spin out in perfectly timed oil slicks. Patterns repeat mechanically as the G-6155 races, explosions mirroring the pits of our drivers eyes. A boat house looms on the horizon as a helicopter blasts impassable craters in the road ahead. Now airborne our driver ignites and spins skyward shrieking as whirling blades & debris plummet toward scorched earth.

Ecstasy. Infectious optimism. Pure Joy. Rick finds a repeating hook at 7:45 that he builds around before an explosion of guitar Rock Goddery. Every time you think he's found the apex of energy within the peak, he unlocks a new level of earworm shredding. He then slows down, brilliantly going back into the earlier riff before deciding to hose down the crowd one last time. This song DELIVERS as a set closer.
Great section later in the jam akin to the Westville "Rockdale," a demented and askew motif thanks to Cotter's urging.
Some heavier riffing in the latter half of the jam makes this version stand out from the 2024 pack.

Equal parts vibesy vibes, angular reverse delay, Big T fulcrum lines, cyclonic tribal toms, digital sauce, and staccato guitar attack, all culminating in a plucked-from-thin-air melody for Rick's closing solo, permuted several times before dissolving into the composed ending. Sultrily stirred.

data.footnote: With Loose Ends tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Typical breakfast for the first 15 or so minutes until the band locks in on a jazz-rock motif similar to "Switchin'." Peter takes an atypically aggressive approach to organ for a sustained peak section that builds momentum to a fever pitch. At Rick's urging, things get heavy through a thrashy peak before things cool off into a final bliss section. Peter makes a valiant attempt at a "Loose Ends" segue but Rick says no and brings us home. Incredible journey.

Spaces out from the initial funk with Peter laying down thick guitar chords. Seems to be firmly sticking to a peaky Type 1.5 zone when a huge build takes a hard left turn into ambient space atop Cotter's churning snare, Trevor colouring with high-register melodies. Rick brings things down into some major-key riffing and Peter picks up the intensity with a turn into klezmer-ish piano jamming.

Two-guitar Goose reflects the first light of sunrise, its shamanic texture a tribute to the crisp dawn. The band patiently floats in that space before shifting into a frenetic and exploratory Ted-like jam. Returning to the song structure, Pete transitions to punctuated keys, inviting Rick into a cyclical step-jam typical of “Madhuvans.” With callbacks to the earlier “Mais Que Nada,” Rick builds to a deliberate peak, both provoked and matched by Trevor’s fierce, Cliff Burton-like bassline.

Another example of quality over quantity - quickly dives into a dark and eerie motif with reverb and delay-drenched clav dominating the space alongside Rick's digital sauce. Gets abandoned a bit prematurely for "No California" but is well worth a listen.

Adventurous version cycles through a few different chord progressions and ideas, but the real landmark moment here is the prominence of Jeff's Bob Weir-like guitar stabs. Very audible on the SBD and a very welcome addition to the improv.

Breathtakingly gorgeous jam and a prime example of what a mid-set "Drip" is capable of. The band relaxes and floats down into a quiet major-key space, Peter colouring around Rick's melodies with serene OB-6 textures. The band displays atypical restraint through the beauty and things eventually come to an end with a hot "Yeti" sandwich.
Aggressive Rick and nice tension-building.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With When The Saints Go Marching In teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Typical 2024 "Saints" jamming hits a solid peak before downshifting into several minutes of cool groovy funk. Peter in particular covers some subtle sonic ground on organ here. The band pivots into bliss and builds beautifully into THE DROP just after 24 minutes. Excellent version that breaks the monotony "Myst" jams had been getting into.
Band slides into a few minutes of dark play in an atypical manner than usual before making a nice "Moby" sandwich.

data.footnote: With You Spin Me Round (Like a Record) and Axel F teases.
data.jamchartnote: RELENTLESS version with "Axel F" and "You Spin Me Round" teases to telegraph the upcoming Halloween show.

Balancing audacity and restraint, this jam showcases Rick’s knack for running wild with freshly unearthed ideas. As the song leaves its post-verse melody, Rick introduces a palm-muted staccato line, tinkering before shifting to double time and weaving it into the opening melody. By 14 minutes, the jam plunges into a darker, synth-laden space, with Cotter steering the refashioned groove into shadowy depths. The melody returns as a blissy yet thunderous psalmic exploration that segues to the composed close.
Cold Rain and Kylie!
data.songname: Can't Get You Out Of My Head

data.jamchartnote: Return of the slow jam for the first time since 2023 languishes in a synth-haze for a while before Cotter picks up the pace and the band unleashes an excellent "Factory Fiction"-like peak.
Sauce over syrup in this version as Rick goes deep into his bag of tricks. Trevor is super active throughout as well.
Much like the 9/26/23 "Yeti" in that it shifts away from typical play into a dance party three-chord jam for its duration.
The last few minutes of this jam feature some of the most gorgeous ambient major-key play from the band to date. Will blow your mind until Rick decides to pull a -> into "White Lights."
Punishing and primal jam that would be right at home in a "Dripfield."

The first half unfolds as quintessential 2024 “Tumble,” delivering its upbeat, major-key, danceable funk. Around 11 minutes, Rick takes the reins, steering into darker, exploratory space. With a probing lead, he unearths a hook, looping and variating it over Cotter’s rolling toms. By 16 minutes, with the sections fully baked, Cotter propels the jam with increased tempo and intricacy. Rick rides the momentum into a sprawling, “So Ready”-styled jam before dropping into “Tumble’s” composed ending.

Barney: “Have you arranged for transportation?” Vivian: “I’m gonna call a cab.” B: “Allow me. Darryl, please take Ms Vivian anywhere she wishes to go… It’s been a pleasure knowing you. Come and visit us again sometime.” V: “Stay cool.” [a montage in the back of the limo set to a haunted descending 3 note pattern as Vivian fondly recalls immolating Edward whilst devouring his skull, arms hugging the human form abdomen and the seed planted within as smoldering eyes glance across the doomed city scrolling by.]
Standard charging bliss until things quiet for the last few minutes. Rick, Peter, and Trevor engage in an intricate dance around each other's melodies with late 2024 maturity.
An early peak leads to Cotter pushing into a double-time groove. Peter gets wild on Moog before the band builds up into a glory zone to close out the set.

Precursor to what will come in Cincy a week later, the band lets the groove dictate where things will go before getting into an excellent peak, though it stays pretty close to "Thatch" form throughout.
Thrashing initial peak breaks into a blissy major key. Rick builds a familiar motif to a second excellent apex before the band executes a surprise segue into "Shama."
Gorgeous slow bliss à la "Morning Dew" patiently develops before fading into "Travelers."
Simple but effective clav riff from Peter informs this always-reliable first set energy boost.
Not your standard "Flo" as the band breaks into a few minutes of dark jamming on the intro.

Incredible example of the November 2024 hey-hole jamming. Riffs get thrown around early by Rick, Peter, and Trevor while Jeff colours on guitar. Pivots from there into a patient peak build that picks up steam and explodes for an awesome finish.

Peter pulls several incredible earworms out of nowhere early on as Rick hangs back on minimalist rhythm. Trevor suggests a progression that will inform the rest of the jam as all five band members listen incredibly closely to each other. The key here is restraint from Rick - and when he finally lets go for the peak, it's nothing short of spectacular. MUST-HEAR.

First significant Boat in a LONG time goes AGGRESSIVE funk. Rick alternates between sharp MuTron and distorted leads while Peter sets up a slick arpeggiator. Punchy Vintage Vibe then carries things before spacing out and coasting atop the twinkling space sounds into an equally as dancey "Fish in the Sea."

Bingo “FITS” finally meets its match, stepping into the ring like Tyson facing Paul. The lockdown-tested heavyweight takes on Cincy’s arpeggiated, perennially online underdog — brimming with digital flair, youthful creativity, nimble footwork, and fog machine bravado. It’s a decision by points, with this scrappy “Fish” revealing new motifs, layers, sounds and overall vibes for one of the best covers in the catalogue.
Deceptively short runtime. The band goes in a different direction than usual and slows things waaaaay down, only to build back up. Really cool use of 15 minutes.

Early aggressive clav work from Peter glides smoothly through a peak before things shift into a contemplative mode. A repeating riff on marimba piano allows for Trevor to really stick out around Cotter's insistent drumming and Rick's subtle riffing.

A thick, grimy soundscape with heavily distorted vibes, Trevor in beast mode, Rick Marshall stack-like overdriven vamping, and a handful of perfectly-placed Jebb bass bombs. A sonic full-frontal assault. If War on Drugs covered “Arrow,” it would sound like this.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Also Sprach Zarathustra tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Part of an absolutely flawless second set, the most adventurous "Engborg" to date explodes out of "Running Up That Hill" as the band plays with dynamics on the jam. Peter adds some synth before Rick pulls us back into peak mode, blows the roof off the Brady Center, and fades unfinished into "Sinnerman."
Eschews the standard 2024 "Saints" motif in favour of a slow and breathtakingly gorgeous jam. Peter leans hard into the Vintage Vibe as Rick pours an incredible amount of emotion into his solo.

data.footnote: With Rick and Trevor on acoustic and a mid-jam switch to electric by Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Mid-jam switch from acoustic to electric by Rick coasts through a solid peak.

At a svelte 15 minutes, one of the year’s most satisfying and efficient performances. Out of the verses, it drops immediately into a patient half-time jam undergirded by sultry organ and Big T funk. Channeling David Gilmour, Rick fills space with the fewest possible notes, crafting an ethereal soundscape. Lead guitar takes to the fore with a bluesy jam that dissolves into a brief Rush-like prog passage before building to a  satisfying tension-and-release peak.

A bonded pair of Entities strafe over the abandoned capital city raining molten cataclysmic destruction and salted earth. Time skipping through the ether bubble we emerge underground to witness VOID then the faint glow of long-dead embers reignited in a haunting pulse of malevolent shades of red and sparkling whites. Coalescing to crystalline form the patterns blink in ancient code as structure takes form stretching outward sprouting into a vast shallow sea of shimmering fractalien beauty. Life finds a way.
Pivots out of funk into excellent full-band bliss.
Early clav funk shifts into an atmospheric zone with excellent chordal work from Jeff on guitar. Rick really pours on the gas toward the end as the explosive peak fades unfinished into "Whip It."
Standard ragefest notable for its dip into Westville "Rockdale" territory for some unsettling runs ahead of the final peak.

Emerges in the midst of the encore to finish the version from earlier in the show, then jams out into some grooving organ funk with Cotter going nuts on his kit. Rick leads confidently into a very different kind of shreddy peak that eventually builds into the finish of "Empress." Really cool and unique space.

First truly adventurous "Arcadia" since 2021 sees the band lead through a bliss section reminiscent of 6/11/21. Huge energy and momentum through a bonus couple minutes of exploration before returning home.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: All the 2024 "Hungersite" jams were leading to this moment. Absolute masterclass in restraint and gradual ramp-up from Cotter as Peter finds a simple phrase on the clav to repeat dreamily for several minutes. When the peak comes, it barely seems like the energy needs to ramp up, but it's just the cathartic conclusion needed. Unfortunate bingo ball pull for "Flodown" can't even dampen the ending.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.footnote: D&B&Flamingos bingo ball. Rick and Peter crowd surfed on inflatable flamingos while the rest of the band played.
data.jamchartnote: With Rick and Peter off on their flamingos, Trevor leads the way with an earworm bass riff atop some excellent aggressive drumming from Cotter and Jeff. The rest of the band eventually returns for the pull of "+14 Minute Jam" where the band heads into some incredible play.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: A dual-part beast that rides the momentum from "Flamingos" into an evil death march. With a mandated amount of time left on the clock, the band builds in unision to a gorgeous bliss peak, breaking for some speed-clav funk ahead of a gradual slowdown and all-timer -> into "Rockdale." Must-hear.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: The moment where the "short jam" clicked for Goose. Coming off of the incredible "+14 Minute Jam," the band gets spacey in the initial funk zone before a BEAUTIFUL transition into a bed of piano-dominated major mode. Builds back into the ending peak from there with nary a wasted second.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: For the first time in a long time, we get dual-guitar "Creatures" jamming - and it's awesome. Gnarly and gritty work from Peter really highlights this dance party.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Peter on guitar for the first time in "Slow," adding an excellent dimension to the arpeggiator jam.
data.venuename: North Charleston Coliseum & Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: Flows out of the song proper like the Anthem encore "reprise" version rather than the usual Vintage Vibe break, creating a different kind of momentum as the band enters the jam. Telepathic interplay on full display through the exploration before segueing -> into "Animal" unfinished.
Breathtakingly gorgeous space-ambient zone at the beginning gives way to a wave of clav. The band's insane level-up of December 2024 in one 14-minute package.

Silky smooth late-2024 transition hardly needs any time within "Thatch" proper before the improv unfurls like a flower into a gorgeous bliss jam. Coasts along effortlessly before dissolving unfinished for the first time ever into an encore break-spanning synth drone.

The late-blooming younger brother of 24's monstrous high-school quarterback and homecoming king, "Cap Drive." The sibling resemblance is unmistabkle, with the same prominent good looks and form. But while 24's two-guitar Goose section immediately unleashes a colossal wall of sound, this one ambles through the halls of adolescent uncertainty before finally finding its senior-year stride — ignited by Rick’s delicate yet forceful guitar-work, Pete’s sudden organ attack, and Cotter’s thunderous drumming.
"Pancakes"-ish major-key peak jam guaranteed to bring a smile to your face with its breakneck momentum.

data.footnote: With Tarantella Napoletana tease from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Rick finds the "Tarantella Napoletana" jam he loves so much in extended versions of "Atlas Dogs" and builds it to a fiery peak. Cools and eventually winds into a beautiful segue -> to a standout "Animal."

The most remarkable thing about this “Animal” is how unexpectedly non-"Animal" it reads. A listener jumping in blindly right after the verses could easily get lost in the sauce of a typical “Arcadia” jam. We find Ricky doing that trademark Ricky thing, with a gradual sustained build patiently transforming a simple musical idea into a high-energy, major-key bliss explosion. This rendition portends of only good things for “Animal," quite possibly as the next big jam vehicle.

data.footnote: The Wood Brothers. Unfinished. With One In, One Out teases.
data.jamchartnote: Most exploratory version to date hangs in some low-key funk out of the gate. Peter hits some squishy synth as Rick takes to wah - but washes of OB-6 quickly spaces things out and the band expands outward into a gorgeous zone where Rick pulls on the "One In, One Out" melody to take us home through a final peak.

Dark and shreddy, Rick really dominates this cool outside-the-box version. Stays in one space for a large portion, and goes, unfinished, into "California Magic" just as it sounds like the band is ready to explore a new idea.

First of two behemoth versions from Winter '25. Two-guitar Goose at its FINEST. Rick and Peter get scratchy as Trevor leads Cotter into a heavy and dark space. From there, it's all-out pandemonium as the band moves from one menacing idea to the next, shifting and evolving through tones as the tension just builds and builds. Explodes into a peaky section as Cotter RELENTLESSLY pushes the pace through the finish.
First show-opening version ever sets the tone for an incredible night with an efficient and well-paced peak jam.

Massive first-set version heads from usual minor-key space into some classic Winter '25 musings, opening way up with dark Rick and Peter. Hits an early peak in a vicious mode before Cotter picks up the pace and things get intensely psychedelic. Reverb clav twines with guitar melodies as the two find a new tension-filled riff and let it simmer and boil before things hit a final wave of tension into the cathartic "EMG" ending. Your jaw will be on the floor.

Celebratory, uplifting, and charging as the band coalesces around a single idea and rips through it in a way that will have you punching the roof of your car in excitement. Phenomenal set-closing peak in an absolutely incredible show that fades out unfinished.

An immediate GOAT contender, this longest-to-date “FITS” sits shoulder to shoulder with Bingo and Taboose versions. The conventional arpeggiated theme and rock-anthem guitar hero riff are swiftly eschewed in favor of a re-sequenced “Stranger Things”-inspired synth line. Pete layers commanding piano and evocative vibes to create a lush sonic bed over which Rick unleashes an expansive solo evoking 90s-era Santana.

First version to break free of its boundaries carries the energy of the surprise jammed-out "FITS" that came right before. Upbeat, rocking, and celebratory, the band never strays too far into the unknown but keeps up some amazing energy throughout before winding its way home. Possibly an indication that there are plans for bigger excursions in the future...

Gets minor, dark, and Westville "Rockdale"-y with all the best notes. Frenetic and uneasy piano gets cloudy among busy work from Rick as Cotter propels the whole thing. Quiets after a spell and seems to be building to a huge major-key explosive finish, but the band stays minor and Peter pours on some distorted clav as they crash through a final peak and fade > to "Dripfield" before you have time to collect your thoughts.

data.footnote: With Shine On You Crazy Diamond teases from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Low-key funk eventually dissolves into a propulsive-yet-ambient space coloured by Peter's reverb clav. Rick goes into his loops as Peter throws out the "Shine On You Crazy Diamond" intro lick before guitar returns to the fray with an intensely psychedelic Mu-Tron peak.

Pretty standard 20-minute peaky "Tumble" gets bolstered by Winter 2025 dissonance seeping into the tension builds toward the end. Would not be notable in 2024 but it's is a different band on this tour.

Cotter is the star in the punishing first half. Once the first peak has been exhausted, the band seems to be setting up a segue but instead opts for several minutes of gorgeous major-key play before cooling off into "A Western Sun."

One of the best "short" jams Goose has ever played. Nasty, dark, brooding - the whole package. We only can dream of where this would have gone beyond 11 minutes, but the band opts to pull into a truncated "Wysteria" somewhat abruptly.
Feel-good disco show-opening jam. No warm-up needed here.

Opening a second set for the first time in nearly two years, "Arc" picks up right where Goosemas and Milwaukee left off with an adventurous jam. While it still retains a sense of the song for its duration, Peter leads the way into intense psychedelia with heavy Moog Muse usage as Rick augments his tone and does the same. Absolutely incredible sustained energy in this one.

Hailing from Canada after its longest gap in several years, this "Hoserwood" delivers "Rosewood's" finest performance since at least the Cap in 2024. Immediately launching into an upbeat, high-energy, hose jam imbued with a bluesy, Allman-esque rock vibe, it eventually downshifts to near silence. From there, a thundering percussive segment builds with a Middle Eastern-accented theme reminiscent of a "Tumble" jam, ultimately ending rather abruptly and unceremoniously.

Breaking the longest stretch on the bench since its debut, this "Flee" departs standard play quickly thanks to Rick diving into loops. Creating a hypnotic atmosphere in tandem with the repeating sounds, Peter lays down some piano riffs as we stretch out. Cotter lays in some excellent cymbal washes before upping the tempo and energy while Rick takes us through a seriously blistering peak. Fades atop the toms and slides -> into "Atlas Dogs."

Pleasant major-key space evolves quickly with Rick on some very purposeful melodic leads overtop Peter's synth drone. Cools from there as the band finds a darker progression, Rick augments his tone, and we're off to the races. Some serious Rick fireworks as the energy ramps up, matched beautifully by Peter's repetitive piano work. Boils into a wild tension-build before coming home strong.

Calls back to the 12/13/24 "Hungersite" in the way that Peter builds a repetitive soaring riff on clav for the first part. The band hits a beautiful peak before cooling into a minute of moody play akin to Ted Tapes cut "Arrokoth" before moving on to "Interlude II."
Major key post-rock progressions into blistering crescendos? Sign us up for MORE. OF. THIS. PLEASE. Absolutely crushed this hallowed cover, making it their own in yet another whole new way.

data.footnote: With Ghostbusters teases from Rick and Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Two-guitar shred with a perfectly-executed "Ghostbusters" tease at the peak. Rolling momentum gets the show started nicely before an ultra clean -> into "Doc Brown."

Even the Benatar cover received a little extra mustard on this night. Peter lays down a bed of synth effects and bouyant vintage vibes for Rick to emote over, delivering a slowly woven lyrical crescendo thematically akin to the Schuyler Sisters theme in Hamilton, notably showcased in "Satisfied".

Some of the best amorphous jamming yet. Fans of the Eugene "Borne" will enjoy this next phase in the evolution of the ambience/texture over melody/structure model. Peter's inpsirational synth work melds with full band to evoke the serene feeling of ice floes in the arctic gently undulating in the waves under the aurora borealis, while a pod of whales calls to the heavens. Rick tugs the OIOO theme back in over this 90's new age excursion in a truly stunning fashion, not a dry eye in the house, into "Animal".

First version to ever open a second set and it's immediately right at home. Absolute two-guitar RAGEFEST cools off juat after the 16min mark but Cotter refuses to let the momentum fade and continues his all-out assault on the toms. Peter makes the switch to piano as Rick throws wah-delay riffs around and things explode through another phenomenal peak. Instead of a quick segue, the band then opts for a few minutes of gorgeous major-key play that acts as a prelude to a fantastic "This Old Sea."

This first “Sea” of ‘25 jettisons the tender vocal reprise that had come to characterize some of ‘24’s finest voyages. The band steers toward the rolling, tempestuous format of past “Seas,” with Rick sprinkling southern rock-tinged runs over Cotter’s crashing waves. Calmer waters welcome a brief but gorgeous buoyant theme that signals landfall via a patient and perfect segue -> to "Creatures."

A "Hot Tea" encore for a Friday rager must be your average dance party...right? This absolutely unhinged version comes complete with Cotter and Trevor solo breaks before diving headlong into Westville "Rockdale" territory for several minutes of sustained dissonance. Just when you think it's time to rip back into the ending, the band finds a new vein of inspiration and continues to pour tension over everything. An all-timer performance.

Repurposing the closing note of "Give It Time" as the first note of a surprise standalone "(dawn)", this unfinished version launches into a freeform jam at the mid-point (similarly to the jammed "SOS" the previous weekend in Milwaukee). Cotter keeps a propulsive gallop running underneath a pensive Allmans-y lead from Rick until a bluesy deconstruction leads into "Echo of a Rose".

This incredibly efficient "Echo" wastes no time moving into the first of several themes explored during a brief but satisfying 12 minutes. Lightning fast and telepathic, the band bobs and weaves under some rare flat-picking from Rick. A rollicking cowbell-infused jam and a spacy meltdown transitioning into "Jive II" round out this quality-over-quantity jam. Don't skip this one!
Another worthy entry into the saga of huge, peaky "Big Modern!" jams. Closes out this first set in style via some extra turns around the heavy ending.
The younger sibling of 11/8/24. Peter summons a sampled ocean wave (no, seriously) and the band builds a linear-yet-exciting jam from nothing to an extended peak that Rick just won't let go.

After an unremarkable first half to this relatively short 14-minute "Pancakes," the bottom half of the stack is downright delicious. Rick does that inimitable Rick thing, taking a simple melody and bending it into a euphoric, blissful segment.  This shines most brightly at the 11:19 and 13:17 marks, where he runs that melody through cascading, waterfalling runs of pure musical liquid.

The band goes HUGE on the encore for the second night in a row. Gets evil from the get-go with POUNDING Trevor and Cotter as Rick and Peter skip their usual spacey antics in favour of angular play. The tempo amps up and we are thrown headlong into Westville "Rockdale"-style space - edge-of-your-seat madness but with Peter on guitar. Trevor dials in synth effects as it gets crazier, the band setting their sights on the ending but getting there by way of several minutes of punishing darkness and wild sounds.
What does disco yacht rock sound like? This is it, and the Mexico crowd eats it up for (most of) their first time seeing this song.

Industrial jammint immediately establishes this debut as an essential part of Goose canon. Things get darker and more robotic, Cotter's pivot to double time really elevating the improv before things go home. The poster child for a more "accessible" version of 2025 two-guitar Goose.

Beautiful, patient segue -> from "Ride Like The Wind." Jam spends some time in the typical major-key "Myst" mode before Peter goes wild on delayed piano. Some cacophony enters as Rick sticks to driving rhythm work. Fantastic peak that gradually winds down over the final few minutes and > to "Give it Time."

Much like the 12/13/24 Hungersite, the band finds a blissful riff early and proceeds to build it patiently and beautifully for the remainder of the jam. Peter and Trevor in particular while Rick shows remarkable restraint in his rhythm playing, and the eventual lead guitar explosion is absolute perfection. Descends into an extended dark section before hitting the changes and coming home.

Auspicious opener that is standard fare until the final segment, where the band descends into a patient, clav-dominated space. Airy melodies take over for several minutes as the band gradually finds their way into "Bob Don."
Feel-good bliss jam foreshadows, like many debut Gonzo versions, where things will go in summer 2025.

data.footnote: With Taylor Goldsmith on guitar and vocals and Griffin Goldsmith on drums.
data.jamchartnote: Taylor and Griffin of Dawes augment this powerful dual-drummer version, which really heats up before Cotter leads the slow-down into a perfect -> through "Rockdale."

Placed within "Empress," the debut of "fast:slow" comes in HOT with one of the craziest feel-good party jams you'll find. Jump up and down for joy with a huge grin on your face as the band unleashes the sheer force of this motif on the Cabo crowd.

Festival-closing insanity. The band dives headlong into breakneck speed Westville "Rockdale" jamming, Rick and Peter in particular chasing each other through a wild tension-filled chase. Trevor uses some deep synth pedals while Cotter propels the whole thing with insistent percussion hits. The evil eventually explodes back into the song proper, but a sly double-time shift on the drums leads to another dip into wild dissonance before coming home. Outstanding version.
Not your average choogle as the band departs CCR proper into a fantastic, driving dual-guitar funk jam. Cotter and Trevor are especially on fire with a locked-in yet fluid pocket. Strap in!

Hits the now-typical "Modern!" bliss zone, following up the peak with a rolling rhythm-centric motif. Rick hangs back more than usual and lets Peter propel things before Cotter blitzes into a renewed peak. Cools and patiently works into a disco groove that -> to "Creatures."
Extra mustard in this version where the whole band really takes extra care to blow up each turn around the tension-builds.
A breathtaking exercise in melodic interplay. Everyone is so active and the ebb and flow of dynamics informs the musical themes of Summer 2025 during the first full show of the tour.
The first in the saga of summer 2025 "Meter Maid" bliss jams. Really amazing full-band jamming around a singular theme that fades somewhat prematurely into "Mr.  Action."

data.footnote: With Crazy Train teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Departs "SALT" proper with excellent momentum from Cotter, Peter laying down JUNO-60 and then OB-6 textures as Rick gets evil. Grounds itself in the second half for some breackneck play before exploding through the finish.

After its tame debut in Mexico, Goose takes "Dustin" for its first proper ride and biggest of the summer. Initial snappy funk is dominated by some subtle and punchy Roland synth work from Peter. The band grooves in this locked-in zone for several minutes before Rick leads things through a major modulation and incredibly patient bliss peak. Pure glory at the end that flows directly into the ending of "Big Modern!" from the night before.
The Goontz is born here as the band toys with the electronic-influenced groove for a while. Never fully materializes and -> to "Echo" somewhat abruptly.

Hearkens back to 7/7/23 at the outset with thick, melodic clav lines from Peter. Transitions into airy, major key jamming - though never hits a true peak - before Rick pulls them into a new, calm space. Building in intensity around a quick-hit motif, the band works in beautiful harmony through a big, explosive passage. Cotter hits the double-time from there for a turn toward the darkness, Trevor leading things into an evil descending progression that sticks around through the explosive "Thatch" ending.

data.footnote: Sergio Mendes. With When The Saints Go Marching In teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: "When The Saints Go Marching In" on crack. An insane amount of frenzy in this short version.
It's the Rick show as he takes his sweet time milking every drop of melodic tension from this jam. Longest and perhaps best of the non-horn versions in Summer '25.

Second-longest jam in the band's history (to date) is really all about the 20+ minute exploration of a single idea - searing, choppy funk with Rick in power stance. When it finally peaks, it's absolutely VOLCANIC.

A pleasing early version featuring a patient, mid-tempo jam that gradually unfolds without ever truly peaking. The middle section leans into a mellow, exploratory groove reminiscent of 2024’s more restrained “Thatches,” with Rick repeating a melodic line that develops steadily over several minutes. Trevor adds depth through artful contrary motion, while Cotter contributes varied, textural fills. The pace quickens as Cotter shifts to double-time, driving an energetic final phase.
Typical blistering "Hungersite" peaking in the first half gives way to the summer's first of two big post-peak motifs - this gritty build very reminiscent of "Factory Fiction."

Rick dives headlong into thick digital sauce as Cotter engages a particularly punishing beat. New veins of wild energy are revealed with each passing minute as the band massively peaks this standout "Drip."

data.footnote: With the original composed bridge for the first time since 3/1/22.
data.jamchartnote: Returning with new lyrics and the original composed section since 3/1/22, the band then opens up the jam into some solid two-guitar bliss play.

DEEP funk in the first half. The band develops a Trevor-forward motif with some amazing support from Peter on second guitar before modulating up into a major key and moving through some layered, airy play. Fades -> to "Factory Fiction."

data.footnote: With Low Rider teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Intense, deeply-layered psychedelic haze develops out of the song proper. A really amazing textural approach that you pretty much never see from Goose resolves beautifully > to "State of the Art."
Coming out of "Psycho Killer," the first proper Goontz jam is seriously excellent. The band completely locks in and Cotter shows off his Disco Biscuits experience with some amazing builds and drops.

Emerging from the Goontz to close an amazing second set, Rick leads the band through several minutes of powerful "Factory" jamming before skipping the easy pull of the ending in favour of evil exploration. Uncovering evil layer after evil layer, the summer 2025 active interplay is on full display here between Rick, Peter, and Trevor. Final section goes into some really out-there choppy play with completely fuzzed-out clav before the band slams back into the "Factory" ending.

Developing out of the funk, Cotter goes into his circular drumming pattern as all four band members engage each other in some beautiful communicative play. Fades before too long into "Running Up That Hill."
Goose stumbles into the riff from the 12/14/24 "B&D&Flamingoes" jam and work it to a frothing full-band peak.

After hinting at a spacious, melodic jam, Rick forgoes Blissisippi and pivots toward a more angular, exploratory space. From there, it becomes the Cotter Ellis Show, with a syncopated, rolling drum assault shaping an undulating back half that resists peaking. The jam eventually dissolves into airy space before dropping into “Madhuvan.”
Pure balls-to-the-walls Goontz.
data.venuename: Everwise Amphitheater at White River State Park

data.jamchartnote: Thumping Vintage Vibe, dominated psychedelia kicks us off for this festival second-set anchoring version. Rick goes heavy into a distorted tone as the band eventually pivots into double-time, building an energetic peak that cools and -> to "Hollywood Nights."

At 13 minutes, the longest “Green River” to date picks up where the San Francisco version left off — opting for Type II (or at least 1.5) exploration over pure choogle. Quickly departing song structure, the jam favors classic-rock–tinged guitar over propulsive drumming and shifting grooves. Though less ambitious than its older sibling, this is another welcome departure from the band’s more straightforward takes on the CCR classic.

First big "AIN" in almost a year sees some beautiful dynamic play from Rick as the band builds from quiet to a melodic peak. The final few minutes, however, are the real star with some contemplative, conversational work as the band works their way > to "Borne."

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Axel F teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: "The Empress of OrGOONTZnos" gets the treatment for the first time, skipping the Peter and Rick solo sections and just going into an all-out dirty dance party with some slick "Axel F" teases from Rick for good measure.
First 20-minute version since 11/16/21 hits a typical rocking peak before the final section goes breakneck speed with stop/start jamming and some of the fastest Rick/Peter play of the tour.

Spacey digital sauce mode resolves into a more grounded jam thanks to Cotter's urging. Rick and Peter meld on some churning guitar themes before working a shorter-than-usual major-key shift. Some great spacey tones and an ascending riff bring us back home.

A pithier (if less adventurous) callback to the PNC “Madhuvan,” this version reprises the A/B sectional approach — oscillating between spacious exploration and heavier, almost metal segments. It dissolves quickly out of the head, with Trevor introducing a melodic idea that Rick runs with, before shifting into the familiar back-and-forth, patiently approaching its composed ending, and morphing seamlessly into “Atlas Dogs.”

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Magic School Bus Theme tease from Peter.
data.jamchartnote: Rick takes the reins and makes another strong entry into the book of Cotter-era bliss "Myst" jams. He finds a melodic hook to build the peak around and just does that, eventually winding down into a calm outro that resolves into "Hungersite."
A longer version than 6/12's, but similar in that it goes straight for the Goontz and doesn't let up for a second.
A brief dip into some blissy major-key play shows where this song can go in the future.
data.venuename: Constellation Brands-Marvin Sands Performing Arts Center

data.footnote: With Into the Myst teases and quotes.
data.jamchartnote: Really cool insertion of the "Myst" ending progression and vocals within this otherwise quick "Rockdale."
data.venuename: Constellation Brands-Marvin Sands Performing Arts Center

data.jamchartnote: The "Rosewood Harp" features Mikaela Davis fluttering around the otherwise-standard jam with some wonderful accents.

Ladies and gentlemen, Trevor Bass. Big T is a monster on this one, introducing a nasty moving-pocket bassline with frills and layers complemented by Cotter’s rolling toms.
