While the first half simmers, the back half’s frenetic guitar line brings the jam to a boil. Peter introduces a thunderous and unexpectedly loud dark synth swell that creates massive tension before releasing into a triumphant, well-earned Lee peak.

Less high-octane and more of a grounded rock jam dominates the first 18 minutes or so, then the band opts for the second huge post-peak "Hungersite" jam of the summer. It's pure Ted Tapes energy, coming close to "Dragonfly" or "Bob Don" with its patient and dreamy vibe - one of the coolest segments of the tour. BEAUTIFUL Trevor.

One of the few “Rockdales” to exceed 20 minutes, this version echoes (almost note-for-note) the circular, melodic, and triumphant force of the 9/7/24 SPAC “Drive,” centering around a repeating earworm that Rick gradually develops. Peter and Trevor support with a steady mid-tempo groove, leaving just enough space for some of Cotter’s most dynamic playing — simultaneously accenting and propelling the jam.

data.footnote: Unfinished. With Wrong Way teases from Rick.
data.jamchartnote: Absolutely incredible upbeat disco build. Rick leads the way and Cotter is right alongside him with some patient builds as they avoid an easy path into the Goontz. Cools after 21 mins as Peter takes out his sequenced percussion loops and Rick and Trevor circle each other's melodies in the open space (with a nice Sublime tease thrown in). Beautifully winds its way -> into an all-timer "Fish in the Sea" from there.

Nice Peter-led jam in the first part splinters into some evil and gritty space thanks to Rick's urging. The band develops a swirling Eastern-style motif from there where Rick somehow resists teasing "Tumble" as things churn and grow in intensity. Seriously fluid transitions between sections as the band shows off their late-tour form. Gets into an ascending theme from there and the band produces a massive peak, flipping the scales after the rage and bringing out a serene, major-key outro.
Statement opener from the band's headline debut at MSG takes its time through some thick, psychedelic swamp jamming.

Second-set opening version at The Garden gets going with some airy sauce from Rick. The band then departs from the funk atop a fluid groove from Cotter and push into a major key. Familiar emotional guitar-led jamming dominates from there, each band member relishing in the accomplishment of this monumental show. Trevor really shines with some active high-register bass lines before things explode back home.

The fish have all fled to the shallows of Kenyir Lake, away from the ominous cold simmer, water molecules violently injected with dark energy shimmering hues of piercing yellow and violet in an eerie churn. A troop of white-thighed surili from the surrounding jungle howl their alarm at witnessing froth and spray cascading into mist filling the Malaysian night sky above with a terrible deadly aura, The Entity conducting this deranged cauldron from the shore like some sort of sadistic sorcerer’s apprentice.

After a loose jam over a funky bassline, the MSGoontz emerges. E-drums and arpeggiated synth textures buoy Rick’s understated, sultry prodding lines. As the groove grows more propulsive, Peter shifts to guitar — his hard-edged rhythm line framing Rick's full-force guitar assault, echoing the JOTY Philly “Tumble” played exactly a year earlier. The song’s triumphant conclusion follows an intervening 20-minute “Creatures” > “Shama.”

Kicking off with all the sonic flair of an Echo & The Bunnymen jamband equivalent, this show-highlight "All I Need" ventures through a highly satisfying section of the sort of low-calorie breezy propulsive bliss jamming that Goose makes look so effortless in 2025. Gorgeous stuff, making for contagious ear-to-ear grins right up through the transition -> "SALT".

Skips the final chorus for the first time ever and instead embarks on the jam from the space-out. Coalescing around Cotter's insistent play, the band builds a ferocious bliss vibe with an intensity found in very few Goose jams. You'll jump through the ceiling with the sheer force of this peak.

Gorgeous segue -> from "A Western Sun." Traverses an incredibly deep terrain for its relatively short 14-minute runtime. The jam grows heavy and punishing, the band taking their time as they work their way into evil territory. Coming up for air, things percolate for a bit before a relatively smooth transition into "Atlas Dogs."

The GOONTZ like it hadn't been played up to this point. No arpeggiator, things move into a heavy disco direction as Peter enters the fray on ring modulator Rhodes. Fantastic exploration of this theme eventually fades > to the ending of "Rockdale."
Fall 2025 was the season for the grimy, back-alley Goontz - and it all starts in this compact rendition.

A rare early first-set jam (for the time period) and the first "Rum" since Viva El Gonzo goes absolutely intergalactic. A maximalist, high-energy jam with fantastic contributions from all members will have you up and dancing for the duration.

data.jamchartnote: The sibling to 2/10/25. Sticks in Cotter's pocket and rides a pulsating wave of Peter's Rhodes through a fluid, psychedelic groove. Some really amazing utilization of delay by Rick leads to a more cacophonous vibe as he and Peter twine their play in an amazing, circular way.

Kicks into a funkier variation on the typical peaky jam at first with Peter suggesting an ascending riff. Rick and Trevor play off of it for a bit before Cotter increases the tempo and things pick up steam. Rick cues multiple modulations with his talkback mic as things continue to build, breezing through a small peak before things flatten out into some punchy synth-driven funk. Toying with a cool bliss progression for a bit, Rick opts to pull into "Loose Ends" in lieu of more jamming.

Coming late in a show light on improv, Goose makes up for lost time with a twisted, dissonant section reminiscent of the Milwaukee and Grand Rapids versions from earlier in the year. From there, Rick executes a smooth modulation to a dreamy major key and Peter works in some subtle Rhodes textures as the bliss jam eventually winds its way home to a hot conclusion.
Solid (if not standard) "Thatch" jamming detours into some evil tension spaces ahead of the final peak.

Makes the expected 2025 move into Goontz territory and beautifully rides that out for a while, but what isn't predictable is the 5.5-minute segue into "Hollywood Nights." No matter how early you hear this coming, it's remarkable to listen as each band member moves toward the Seger cover bit by bit, in zero hurry.

Rick once again grasps melody from thin air, introducing the central musical idea early in the jam. The rhythm section take a no holds barred approach from the jump, buoyed but Cotter’s unstoppable motor. Rick and Peter slowly develop the musical idea into what eventually sounds like a composed piece of music. Lots of big ascending riff energy throughout with bits of triumph alongside a constant pummeling of drums and an enormous peak. If you like the drums, this Lee is for you.

After spending most of the year riddled with ripcords and unfinished ideas, the 2025 "Wysteria" finally arrives in Shohio. Churning dual-guitar improv starts us off, Trevor hammering in the low end as Rick and Peter battle it out. Smoothly transitions to major in a move akin to the Alpharetta "Madhuvan" (though arguably much more cohesive) and blossoms into a gorgeous, deep peak.

Detours from the "Tarantella"-adjacent jamming in the final few minutes for some crazed, dissonant spiraling. Really cool flange effect from Rick gives a new dimension over Cotter's insistent snare rolling that then downshifts into a half-time conclusion.

Emerges out of "Dim Lights" with an intro jam that is some of the grimiest Goontz yet. Peter steps to the front on ring modulator Rhodes as tension builds before sliding smoothly into the song proper. While some "standard" Goontz could be expected later on, the band takes several detours into some darker, atypical zones before bringing it home.

An unusually soft and contemplative approach to the jam at first. Trevor is the lead instrument here, laying down gorgeous melodies. When Rick asserts himself, Trevor is right there matching and augmenting the musical ideas. The familiar slow build picks up more and more steam as Cotter gradually increases the intensity until we find ourselves in a typically fiery Hungersite jam that takes a shocking turn into Make The Move.

Cotter and Rick usher the band away from the song structure with hyper speed snare and a barrage of notes, respectively. This continues for a few minutes before the jam dissolves, finding the same contemplative space established earlier in Hungersite, but only for a moment. Rick and Trevor chase each other into a terrifying labyrinth of fear, constantly building tension but it goes unresolved as the band drops into Dripfield to complete the Driptych.
Gets a jam for the first time ever instead of dropping into Part II. Nothing crazy improvisationally, just a well-executed peak with some great Trevor work that hints at "Drive" before concluding.
